2257  switch (Opc) {
2258  default: llvm_unreachable("Unreachable!");
2259  case X86::MOVHLPSrr: Opc = X86::UNPCKHPDrr; break;
2260  case X86::UNPCKHPDrr: Opc = X86::MOVHLPSrr; break;
2261  case X86::VMOVHLPSrr: Opc = X86::VUNPCKHPDrr; break;

2271  case X86::CMOV16rr: case X86::CMOV32rr: case X86::CMOV64rr: {
2272  auto &WorkingMI = cloneIfNew(MI);
2273  unsigned OpNo = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands() - 1;
2274  X86::CondCode CC = static_cast<X86::CondCode>(MI.getOperand(OpNo).getImm());
2275  WorkingMI.getOperand(OpNo).setImm(X86::GetOppositeBranchCondition(CC));
2276  return TargetInstrInfo::commuteInstructionImpl(WorkingMI, /*NewMI=*/false,
2277  OpIdx1, OpIdx2);
2278  }
2279  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrri: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmi:
2280  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmi:
2281  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmi:

2283  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmi:
2284  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmi:
2285  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrrik:

2287  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rrik:
2288  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrrik:
2289  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rrik:
2290  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rrik:
2291  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmikz:
2292  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmikz:
2293  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmikz:
2294  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmikz:
2295  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmikz:
2296  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmikz:
2297  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmbi:
2298  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmbi:
2299  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmbi:
2300  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmbi:
2301  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmbi:
2302  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmbi:
2303  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmbikz:
2304  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmbikz:
2305  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmbikz:
2306  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmbikz:
2307  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmbikz:
2308  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmbikz: {
2309  auto &WorkingMI = cloneIfNew(MI);
2310  commuteVPTERNLOG(WorkingMI, OpIdx1, OpIdx2);
2311  return TargetInstrInfo::commuteInstructionImpl(WorkingMI, /*NewMI=*/false,
2312  OpIdx1, OpIdx2);
2313  }
2314  default: {
2315  if (isCommutableVPERMV3Instruction(MI.getOpcode())) {
2316  unsigned Opc = getCommutedVPERMV3Opcode(MI.getOpcode());
2317  auto &WorkingMI = cloneIfNew(MI);
2318  WorkingMI.setDesc(get(Opc));
2319  return TargetInstrInfo::commuteInstructionImpl(WorkingMI, /*NewMI=*/false,
2320  OpIdx1, OpIdx2);
2321  }
2322 
2323  const X86InstrFMA3Group *FMA3Group = getFMA3Group(MI.getOpcode(),
2324  MI.getDesc().TSFlags);
2325  if (FMA3Group) {
2326  unsigned Opc =
2327  getFMA3OpcodeToCommuteOperands(MI, OpIdx1, OpIdx2, *FMA3Group);
2328  auto &WorkingMI = cloneIfNew(MI);
2329  WorkingMI.setDesc(get(Opc));
2330  return TargetInstrInfo::commuteInstructionImpl(WorkingMI, /*NewMI=*/false,
2331  OpIdx1, OpIdx2);
2332  }
2333 
2334  return TargetInstrInfo::commuteInstructionImpl(MI, NewMI, OpIdx1, OpIdx2);
2335  }
2336  }
2337 }
2338 
2339 bool
2340 X86InstrInfo::findThreeSrcCommutedOpIndices(const MachineInstr &MI,
2341  unsigned &SrcOpIdx1,
2342  unsigned &SrcOpIdx2,
2343  bool IsIntrinsic) const {
2344  uint64_t TSFlags = MI.getDesc().TSFlags;
2345 
2346  unsigned FirstCommutableVecOp = 1;
2347  unsigned LastCommutableVecOp = 3;
2348  unsigned KMaskOp = -1U;
2349  if (X86II::isKMasked(TSFlags)) {
2350  // For k-zero-masked operations it is Ok to commute the first vector
2351  // operand. Unless this is an intrinsic instruction.
2352  // For regular k-masked operations a conservative choice is done as the
2353  // elements of the first vector operand, for which the corresponding bit
2354  // in the k-mask operand is set to 0, are copied to the result of the
2355  // instruction.
2356  // TODO/FIXME: The commute still may be legal if it is known that the
2357  // k-mask operand is set to either all ones or all zeroes.
2358  // It is also Ok to commute the 1st operand if all users of MI use only
2359  // the elements enabled by the k-mask operand. For example,
2360  // v4 = VFMADD213PSZrk v1, k, v2, v3; // v1[i] = k[i] ? v2[i]*v1[i]+v3[i]
2361  // : v1[i];
2362  // VMOVAPSZmrk <mem_addr>, k, v4; // this is the ONLY user of v4 ->
2363  // // Ok, to commute v1 in FMADD213PSZrk.
2364 
2365  // The k-mask operand has index = 2 for masked and zero-masked operations.
2366  KMaskOp = 2;
2367 
2368  // The operand with index = 1 is used as a source for those elements for
2369  // which the corresponding bit in the k-mask is set to 0.
2370  if (X86II::isKMergeMasked(TSFlags) || IsIntrinsic)
2371  FirstCommutableVecOp = 3;
2372 
2373  LastCommutableVecOp++;
2374  } else if (IsIntrinsic) {
2375  // Commuting the first operand of an intrinsic instruction isn't possible
2376  // unless we can prove that only the lowest element of the result is used.
2377  FirstCommutableVecOp = 2;
2378  }
2379 
2380  if (isMem(MI, LastCommutableVecOp))
2381  LastCommutableVecOp--;
2382 
2383  // Only the first RegOpsNum operands are commutable.
2384  // Also, the value 'CommuteAnyOperandIndex' is valid here as it means
2385  // that the operand is not specified/fixed.
2386  if (SrcOpIdx1 != CommuteAnyOperandIndex &&
2387  (SrcOpIdx1 < FirstCommutableVecOp || SrcOpIdx1 > LastCommutableVecOp ||
2388  SrcOpIdx1 == KMaskOp))
2389  return false;
2390  if (SrcOpIdx2 != CommuteAnyOperandIndex &&
2391  (SrcOpIdx2 < FirstCommutableVecOp || SrcOpIdx2 > LastCommutableVecOp ||
2392  SrcOpIdx2 == KMaskOp))
2393  return false;
2394 
2395  // Look for two different register operands assumed to be commutable
2396  // regardless of the FMA opcode. The FMA opcode is adjusted later.
2397  if (SrcOpIdx1 == CommuteAnyOperandIndex ||
2398  SrcOpIdx2 == CommuteAnyOperandIndex) {
2399  unsigned CommutableOpIdx2 = SrcOpIdx2;
2400 
2401  // At least one of operands to be commuted is not specified and
2402  // this method is free to choose appropriate commutable operands.
2403  if (SrcOpIdx1 == SrcOpIdx2)
2404  // Both of operands are not fixed. By default set one of commutable
2405  // operands to the last register operand of the instruction.
2406  CommutableOpIdx2 = LastCommutableVecOp;
2407  else if (SrcOpIdx2 == CommuteAnyOperandIndex)
2408  // Only one of operands is not fixed.
2409  CommutableOpIdx2 = SrcOpIdx1;
2410 
2411  // CommutableOpIdx2 is well defined now. Let's choose another commutable
2412  // operand and assign its index to CommutableOpIdx1.
2413  Register Op2Reg = MI.getOperand(CommutableOpIdx2).getReg();
2414 
2415  unsigned CommutableOpIdx1;
2416  for (CommutableOpIdx1 = LastCommutableVecOp;
2417  CommutableOpIdx1 >= FirstCommutableVecOp; CommutableOpIdx1--) {
2418  // Just ignore and skip the k-mask operand.
2419  if (CommutableOpIdx1 == KMaskOp)
2420  continue;
2421 
2422  // The commuted operands must have different registers.
2423  // Otherwise, the commute transformation does not change anything and
2424  // is useless then.
2425  if (Op2Reg != MI.getOperand(CommutableOpIdx1).getReg())
2426  break;
2427  }
2428 
2429  // No appropriate commutable operands were found.
2430  if (CommutableOpIdx1 < FirstCommutableVecOp)
2431  return false;
2432 
2433  // Assign the found pair of commutable indices to SrcOpIdx1 and SrcOpidx2
2434  // to return those values.
2435  if (!fixCommutedOpIndices(SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2,
2436  CommutableOpIdx1, CommutableOpIdx2))
2437  return false;
2438  }
2439 
2440  return true;
2441 }
2442 
2443 bool X86InstrInfo::findCommutedOpIndices(const MachineInstr &MI,
2444  unsigned &SrcOpIdx1,
2445  unsigned &SrcOpIdx2) const {
2446  const MCInstrDesc &Desc = MI.getDesc();
2447  if (!Desc.isCommutable())
2448  return false;
2449 
2450  switch (MI.getOpcode()) {
2451  case X86::CMPSDrr:
2452  case X86::CMPSSrr:
2453  case X86::CMPPDrri:
2454  case X86::CMPPSrri:
2455  case X86::VCMPSDrr:
2456  case X86::VCMPSSrr:
2457  case X86::VCMPPDrri:
2458  case X86::VCMPPSrri:
2459  case X86::VCMPPDYrri:
2460  case X86::VCMPPSYrri:
2461  case X86::VCMPSDZrr:
2462  case X86::VCMPSSZrr:
2463  case X86::VCMPPDZrri:
2464  case X86::VCMPPSZrri:
2465  case X86::VCMPSHZrr:
2466  case X86::VCMPPHZrri:
2467  case X86::VCMPPHZ128rri:
2468  case X86::VCMPPHZ256rri:
2469  case X86::VCMPPDZ128rri:
2470  case X86::VCMPPSZ128rri:
2471  case X86::VCMPPDZ256rri:
2472  case X86::VCMPPSZ256rri:
2473  case X86::VCMPPDZrrik:
2474  case X86::VCMPPSZrrik:
2475  case X86::VCMPPDZ128rrik:
2476  case X86::VCMPPSZ128rrik:
2477  case X86::VCMPPDZ256rrik:
2478  case X86::VCMPPSZ256rrik: {
2479  unsigned OpOffset = X86II::isKMasked(Desc.TSFlags) ? 1 : 0;
2480 
2481  // Float comparison can be safely commuted for
2482  // Ordered/Unordered/Equal/NotEqual tests
2483  unsigned Imm = MI.getOperand(3 + OpOffset).getImm() & 0x7;
2484  switch (Imm) {
2485  default:
2486  // EVEX versions can be commuted.
2487  if ((Desc.TSFlags & X86II::EncodingMask) == X86II::EVEX)
2488  break;
2489  return false;
2490  case 0x00: // EQUAL
2491  case 0x03: // UNORDERED
2492  case 0x04: // NOT EQUAL
2493  case 0x07: // ORDERED
2494  break;
2495  }
2496 
2497  // The indices of the commutable operands are 1 and 2 (or 2 and 3
2498  // when masked).
2499  // Assign them to the returned operand indices here.
2500  return fixCommutedOpIndices(SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2, 1 + OpOffset,
2501  2 + OpOffset);
2502  }
2503  case X86::MOVSSrr:
2504  // X86::MOVSDrr is always commutable. MOVSS is only commutable if we can
2505  // form sse4.1 blend. We assume VMOVSSrr/VMOVSDrr is always commutable since
2506  // AVX implies sse4.1.
2507  if (Subtarget.hasSSE41())
2508  return TargetInstrInfo::findCommutedOpIndices(MI, SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2);
2509  return false;
2510  case X86::SHUFPDrri:
2511  // We can commute this to MOVSD.
2512  if (MI.getOperand(3).getImm() == 0x02)
2513  return TargetInstrInfo::findCommutedOpIndices(MI, SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2);
2514  return false;
2515  case X86::MOVHLPSrr:
2516  case X86::UNPCKHPDrr:
2517  case X86::VMOVHLPSrr:
2518  case X86::VUNPCKHPDrr:
2519  case X86::VMOVHLPSZrr:
2520  case X86::VUNPCKHPDZ128rr:
2521  if (Subtarget.hasSSE2())
2522  return TargetInstrInfo::findCommutedOpIndices(MI, SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2);
2523  return false;
2524  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrri: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmi:
2525  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmi:
2526  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmi:
2527  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrri: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmi:
2528  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmi:
2529  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rri: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmi:
2530  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrrik:
2531  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rrik:
2532  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rrik:
2533  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrrik:
2534  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rrik:
2535  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rrik:
2536  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmikz:
2537  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmikz:
2538  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmikz:
2539  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmikz:
2540  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmikz:
2541  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rrikz: case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmikz:
2542  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmbi:
2543  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmbi:
2544  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmbi:
2545  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmbi:
2546  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmbi:
2547  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmbi:
2548  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ128rmbikz:
2549  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZ256rmbikz:
2550  case X86::VPTERNLOGDZrmbikz:
2551  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ128rmbikz:
2552  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZ256rmbikz:
2553  case X86::VPTERNLOGQZrmbikz:
2554  return findThreeSrcCommutedOpIndices(MI, SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2);
2555  case X86::VPDPWSSDYrr:
2556  case X86::VPDPWSSDrr:
2557  case X86::VPDPWSSDSYrr:
2558  case X86::VPDPWSSDSrr:
2559  case X86::VPDPBSSDSrr:
2560  case X86::VPDPBSSDSYrr:
2561  case X86::VPDPBSSDrr:
2562  case X86::VPDPBSSDYrr:
2563  case X86::VPDPBUUDSrr:
2564  case X86::VPDPBUUDSYrr:
2565  case X86::VPDPBUUDrr:
2566  case X86::VPDPBUUDYrr:
2567  case X86::VPDPWSSDZ128r:
2568  case X86::VPDPWSSDZ128rk:
2569  case X86::VPDPWSSDZ128rkz:
2570  case X86::VPDPWSSDZ256r:
2571  case X86::VPDPWSSDZ256rk:
2572  case X86::VPDPWSSDZ256rkz:
2573  case X86::VPDPWSSDZr:
2574  case X86::VPDPWSSDZrk:
2575  case X86::VPDPWSSDZrkz:
2576  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZ128r:
2577  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZ128rk:
2578  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZ128rkz:
2579  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZ256r:
2580  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZ256rk:
2581  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZ256rkz:
2582  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZr:
2583  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZrk:
2584  case X86::VPDPWSSDSZrkz:
2585  case X86::VPMADD52HUQrr:
2586  case X86::VPMADD52HUQYrr:
2587  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZ128r:
2588  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZ128rk:
2589  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZ128rkz:
2590  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZ256r:
2591  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZ256rk:
2592  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZ256rkz:
2593  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZr:
2594  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZrk:
2595  case X86::VPMADD52HUQZrkz:
2596  case X86::VPMADD52LUQrr:
2597  case X86::VPMADD52LUQYrr:
2598  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZ128r:
2599  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZ128rk:
2600  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZ128rkz:
2601  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZ256r:
2602  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZ256rk:
2603  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZ256rkz:
2604  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZr:
2605  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZrk:
2606  case X86::VPMADD52LUQZrkz:
2607  case X86::VFMADDCPHZr:
2608  case X86::VFMADDCPHZrk:
2609  case X86::VFMADDCPHZrkz:
2610  case X86::VFMADDCPHZ128r:
2611  case X86::VFMADDCPHZ128rk:
2612  case X86::VFMADDCPHZ128rkz:
2613  case X86::VFMADDCPHZ256r:
2614  case X86::VFMADDCPHZ256rk:
2615  case X86::VFMADDCPHZ256rkz:
2616  case X86::VFMADDCSHZr:
2617  case X86::VFMADDCSHZrk:
2618  case X86::VFMADDCSHZrkz: {
2619  unsigned CommutableOpIdx1 = 2;
2620  unsigned CommutableOpIdx2 = 3;
2621  if (X86II::isKMasked(Desc.TSFlags)) {
2622  // Skip the mask register.
2623  ++CommutableOpIdx1;
2624  ++CommutableOpIdx2;
2625  }
2626  if (!fixCommutedOpIndices(SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2,
2627  CommutableOpIdx1, CommutableOpIdx2))
2628  return false;
2629  if (!MI.getOperand(SrcOpIdx1).isReg() ||
2630  !MI.getOperand(SrcOpIdx2).isReg())
2631  // No idea.
2632  return false;
2633  return true;
2634  }
2635 
2636  default:
2637  const X86InstrFMA3Group *FMA3Group = getFMA3Group(MI.getOpcode(),
2638  MI.getDesc().TSFlags);
2639  if (FMA3Group)
2640  return findThreeSrcCommutedOpIndices(MI, SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2,
2641  FMA3Group->isIntrinsic());
2642 
2643  // Handled masked instructions since we need to skip over the mask input
2644  // and the preserved input.
2645  if (X86II::isKMasked(Desc.TSFlags)) {
2646  // First assume that the first input is the mask operand and skip past it.
2647  unsigned CommutableOpIdx1 = Desc.getNumDefs() + 1;
2648  unsigned CommutableOpIdx2 = Desc.getNumDefs() + 2;
2649  // Check if the first input is tied. If there isn't one then we only
2650  // need to skip the mask operand which we did above.
2651  if ((MI.getDesc().getOperandConstraint(Desc.getNumDefs(),
2652  MCOI::TIED_TO) != -1)) {
2653  // If this is zero masking instruction with a tied operand, we need to
2654  // move the first index back to the first input since this must
2655  // be a 3 input instruction and we want the first two non-mask inputs.
2656  // Otherwise this is a 2 input instruction with a preserved input and
2657  // mask, so we need to move the indices to skip one more input.
2658  if (X86II::isKMergeMasked(Desc.TSFlags)) {
2659  ++CommutableOpIdx1;
2660  ++CommutableOpIdx2;
2661  } else {
2662  --CommutableOpIdx1;
2663  }
2664  }
2665 
2666  if (!fixCommutedOpIndices(SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2,
2667  CommutableOpIdx1, CommutableOpIdx2))
2668  return false;
2669 
2670  if (!MI.getOperand(SrcOpIdx1).isReg() ||
2671  !MI.getOperand(SrcOpIdx2).isReg())
2672  // No idea.
2673  return false;
2674  return true;
2675  }
2676 
2677  return TargetInstrInfo::findCommutedOpIndices(MI, SrcOpIdx1, SrcOpIdx2);
2678  }
2679  return false;
2680 }
2681 
2682 static bool isConvertibleLEA(MachineInstr *MI) {
2683  unsigned Opcode = MI->getOpcode();
2684  if (Opcode != X86::LEA32r && Opcode != X86::LEA64r &&
2685  Opcode != X86::LEA64_32r)
2686  return false;
2687 
2688  const MachineOperand &Scale = MI->getOperand(1 + X86::AddrScaleAmt);
2689  const MachineOperand &Disp = MI->getOperand(1 + X86::AddrDisp);
2690  const MachineOperand &Segment = MI->getOperand(1 + X86::AddrSegmentReg);
2691 
2692  if (Segment.getReg() != 0 || !Disp.isImm() || Disp.getImm() != 0 ||
2693  Scale.getImm() > 1)
2694  return false;
2695 
2696  return true;
2697 }
2698 
2699 bool X86InstrInfo::hasCommutePreference(MachineInstr &MI, bool &Commute) const {
2700  // Currently we're interested in following sequence only.
2701  // r3 = lea r1, r2
2702  // r5 = add r3, r4
2703  // Both r3 and r4 are killed in add, we hope the add instruction has the
2704  // operand order
2705  // r5 = add r4, r3
2706  // So later in X86FixupLEAs the lea instruction can be rewritten as add.
2707  unsigned Opcode = MI.getOpcode();
2708  if (Opcode != X86::ADD32rr && Opcode != X86::ADD64rr)
2709  return false;
2710 
2711  const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MI.getParent()->getParent()->getRegInfo();
2712  Register Reg1 = MI.getOperand(1).getReg();
2713  Register Reg2 = MI.getOperand(2).getReg();
2714 
2715  // Check if Reg1 comes from LEA in the same MBB.
2716  if (MachineInstr *Inst = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Reg1)) {
2717  if (isConvertibleLEA(Inst) && Inst->getParent() == MI.getParent()) {
2718  Commute = true;
2719  return true;
2720  }
2721  }
2722 
2723  // Check if Reg2 comes from LEA in the same MBB.
2724  if (MachineInstr *Inst = MRI.getUniqueVRegDef(Reg2)) {
2725  if (isConvertibleLEA(Inst) && Inst->getParent() == MI.getParent()) {
2726  Commute = false;
2727  return true;
2728  }
2729  }
2730 
2731  return false;
2732 }
2733 
2734 int X86::getCondSrcNoFromDesc(const MCInstrDesc &MCID) {
2735  unsigned Opcode = MCID.getOpcode();
2736  if (!(X86::isJCC(Opcode) || X86::isSETCC(Opcode) || X86::isCMOVCC(Opcode)))
2737  return -1;
2738  // Assume that condition code is always the last use operand.
2739  unsigned NumUses = MCID.getNumOperands() - MCID.getNumDefs();
2740  return NumUses - 1;
2741 }
2742 
2743 X86::CondCode X86::getCondFromMI(const MachineInstr &MI) {
2744  const MCInstrDesc &MCID = MI.getDesc();
2745  int CondNo = getCondSrcNoFromDesc(MCID);
2746  if (CondNo < 0)
2747  return X86::COND_INVALID;
2748  CondNo += MCID.getNumDefs();
2749  return static_cast<X86::CondCode>(MI.getOperand(CondNo).getImm());
2750 }

2752 X86::CondCode X86::getCondFromBranch(const MachineInstr &MI) {
2753  return X86::isJCC(MI.getOpcode()) ? X86::getCondFromMI(MI)
2754  : X86::COND_INVALID;
2755 }

2757 X86::CondCode X86::getCondFromSETCC(const MachineInstr &MI) {

2759  : X86::COND_INVALID;
2760 }

2762 X86::CondCode X86::getCondFromCMov(const MachineInstr &MI) {
2763  return X86::isCMOVCC(MI.getOpcode()) ? X86::getCondFromMI(MI)
2764  : X86::COND_INVALID;
2765 }

2767 /// Return the inverse of the specified condition,
2768 /// e.g. turning COND_E to COND_NE.
2769 X86::CondCode X86::GetOppositeBranchCondition(X86::CondCode CC) {
2770  switch (CC) {
2771  default: llvm_unreachable("Illegal condition code!");
2772  case X86::COND_E: return X86::COND_NE;
2773  case X86::COND_NE: return X86::COND_E;
2774  case X86::COND_L: return X86::COND_GE;
2775  case X86::COND_LE: return X86::COND_G;
2776  case X86::COND_G: return X86::COND_LE;
2777  case X86::COND_GE: return X86::COND_L;
2778  case X86::COND_B: return X86::COND_AE;
2779  case X86::COND_BE: return X86::COND_A;
2780  case X86::COND_A: return X86::COND_BE;
2781  case X86::COND_AE: return X86::COND_B;
2782  case X86::COND_S: return X86::COND_NS;
2783  case X86::COND_NS: return X86::COND_S;
2784  case X86::COND_P: return X86::COND_NP;
2785  case X86::COND_NP: return X86::COND_P;
2786  case X86::COND_O: return X86::COND_NO;
2787  case X86::COND_NO: return X86::COND_O;
2788  case X86::COND_NE_OR_P: return X86::COND_E_AND_NP;
2789  case X86::COND_E_AND_NP: return X86::COND_NE_OR_P;
2790  }
2791 }

2793 /// Assuming the flags are set by MI(a,b), return the condition code if we
2794 /// modify the instructions such that flags are set by MI(b,a).
2795 static X86::CondCode getSwappedCondition(X86::CondCode CC) {
2796  switch (CC) {
2797  default: return X86::COND_INVALID;
2798  case X86::COND_E: return X86::COND_E;
2799  case X86::COND_NE: return X86::COND_NE;
2800  case X86::COND_L: return X86::COND_G;
2801  case X86::COND_LE: return X86::COND_GE;
2802  case X86::COND_G: return X86::COND_L;
2803  case X86::COND_GE: return X86::COND_LE;
2804  case X86::COND_B: return X86::COND_A;
2805  case X86::COND_BE: return X86::COND_AE;
2806  case X86::COND_A: return X86::COND_B;
2807  case X86::COND_AE: return X86::COND_BE;
2808  }
2809 }

2811 std::pair<X86::CondCode, bool>
2812 X86::getX86ConditionCode(CmpInst::Predicate Predicate) {
2813  X86::CondCode CC = X86::COND_INVALID;
2814  bool NeedSwap = false;
2815  switch (Predicate) {
2816  default: break;
2817  // Floating-point Predicates
2818  case CmpInst::FCMP_UEQ: CC = X86::COND_E; break;
2819  case CmpInst::FCMP_OLT: NeedSwap = true; [[fallthrough]];
2820  case CmpInst::FCMP_OGT: CC = X86::COND_A; break;
2821  case CmpInst::FCMP_OLE: NeedSwap = true; [[fallthrough]];
2822  case CmpInst::FCMP_OGE: CC = X86::COND_AE; break;
2823  case CmpInst::FCMP_UGT: NeedSwap = true; [[fallthrough]];
2824  case CmpInst::FCMP_ULT: CC = X86::COND_B; break;
2825  case CmpInst::FCMP_UGE: NeedSwap = true; [[fallthrough]];
2826  case CmpInst::FCMP_ULE: CC = X86::COND_BE; break;
2827  case CmpInst::FCMP_ONE: CC = X86::COND_NE; break;
2828  case CmpInst::FCMP_UNO: CC = X86::COND_P; break;
2829  case CmpInst::FCMP_ORD: CC = X86::COND_NP; break;
2830  case CmpInst::FCMP_OEQ: [[fallthrough]];
2831  case CmpInst::FCMP_UNE: CC = X86::COND_INVALID; break;
2832 
2833  // Integer Predicates
2834  case CmpInst::ICMP_EQ: CC = X86::COND_E; break;
2835  case CmpInst::ICMP_NE: CC = X86::COND_NE; break;
2836  case CmpInst::ICMP_UGT: CC = X86::COND_A; break;
2837  case CmpInst::ICMP_UGE: CC = X86::COND_AE; break;
2838  case CmpInst::ICMP_ULT: CC = X86::COND_B; break;
2839  case CmpInst::ICMP_ULE: CC = X86::COND_BE; break;
2840  case CmpInst::ICMP_SGT: CC = X86::COND_G; break;
2841  case CmpInst::ICMP_SGE: CC = X86::COND_GE; break;
2842  case CmpInst::ICMP_SLT: CC = X86::COND_L; break;
2843  case CmpInst::ICMP_SLE: CC = X86::COND_LE; break;
2844  }
2845 
2846  return std::make_pair(CC, NeedSwap);
2847 }
2848 
2849 /// Return a cmov opcode for the given register size in bytes, and operand type.
2850 unsigned X86::getCMovOpcode(unsigned RegBytes, bool HasMemoryOperand) {
2851  switch(RegBytes) {
2852  default: llvm_unreachable("Illegal register size!");
2853  case 2: return HasMemoryOperand ? X86::CMOV16rm : X86::CMOV16rr;
2854  case 4: return HasMemoryOperand ? X86::CMOV32rm : X86::CMOV32rr;
2855  case 8: return HasMemoryOperand ? X86::CMOV64rm : X86::CMOV64rr;
2856  }
2857 }

2859 /// Get the VPCMP immediate for the given condition.
2860 unsigned X86::getVPCMPImmForCond(ISD::CondCode CC) {
2861  switch (CC) {
2862  default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected SETCC condition");
2863  case ISD::SETNE: return 4;
2864  case ISD::SETEQ: return 0;
2865  case ISD::SETULT:
2866  case ISD::SETLT: return 1;
2867  case ISD::SETUGT:
2868  case ISD::SETGT: return 6;
2869  case ISD::SETUGE:
2870  case ISD::SETGE: return 5;
2871  case ISD::SETULE:
2872  case ISD::SETLE: return 2;
2873  }
2874 }
2875 
2876 /// Get the VPCMP immediate if the operands are swapped.
2877 unsigned X86::getSwappedVPCMPImm(unsigned Imm) {
2878  switch (Imm) {
2879  default: llvm_unreachable("Unreachable!");
2880  case 0x01: Imm = 0x06; break; // LT -> NLE
2881  case 0x02: Imm = 0x05; break; // LE -> NLT
2882  case 0x05: Imm = 0x02; break; // NLT -> LE
2883  case 0x06: Imm = 0x01; break; // NLE -> LT
2884  case 0x00: // EQ
2885  case 0x03: // FALSE
2886  case 0x04: // NE
2887  case 0x07: // TRUE
2888  break;
2889  }
2890 
2891  return Imm;
2892 }
2893 
2894 /// Get the VPCOM immediate if the operands are swapped.
2895 unsigned X86::getSwappedVPCOMImm(unsigned Imm) {
2896  switch (Imm) {
2897  default: llvm_unreachable("Unreachable!");
2898  case 0x00: Imm = 0x02; break; // LT -> GT
2899  case 0x01: Imm = 0x03; break; // LE -> GE
2900  case 0x02: Imm = 0x00; break; // GT -> LT
2901  case 0x03: Imm = 0x01; break; // GE -> LE
2902  case 0x04: // EQ
2903  case 0x05: // NE
2904  case 0x06: // FALSE
2905  case 0x07: // TRUE
2906  break;
2907  }
2908 
2909  return Imm;
2910 }
2911 
2912 /// Get the VCMP immediate if the operands are swapped.
2913 unsigned X86::getSwappedVCMPImm(unsigned Imm) {
2914  // Only need the lower 2 bits to distinquish.
2915  switch (Imm & 0x3) {
2916  default: llvm_unreachable("Unreachable!");
2917  case 0x00: case 0x03:
2918  // EQ/NE/TRUE/FALSE/ORD/UNORD don't change immediate when commuted.
2919  break;
2920  case 0x01: case 0x02:
2921  // Need to toggle bits 3:0. Bit 4 stays the same.
2922  Imm ^= 0xf;
2923  break;
2924  }
2925 
2926  return Imm;
2927 }
2928 
2929 /// Return true if the Reg is X87 register.
2930 static bool isX87Reg(unsigned Reg) {
2931  return (Reg == X86::FPCW || Reg == X86::FPSW ||
2932  (Reg >= X86::ST0 && Reg <= X86::ST7));
2933 }
2934 
2935 /// check if the instruction is X87 instruction
2936 bool X86::isX87Instruction(MachineInstr &MI) {
2937  for (const MachineOperand &MO : MI.operands()) {
2938  if (!MO.isReg())
2939  continue;
2940  if (isX87Reg(MO.getReg()))
2941  return true;
2942  }
2943  return false;
2944 }

2946 bool X86InstrInfo::isUnconditionalTailCall(const MachineInstr &MI) const {
2947  switch (MI.getOpcode()) {
2948  case X86::TCRETURNdi:
2949  case X86::TCRETURNri:
2950  case X86::TCRETURNmi:
2951  case X86::TCRETURNdi64:
2952  case X86::TCRETURNri64:
2953  case X86::TCRETURNmi64:
2954  return true;
2955  default:
2956  return false;
2957  }
2958 }
2959 
2960 bool X86InstrInfo::canMakeTailCallConditional(
2961  SmallVectorImpl<MachineOperand> &BranchCond,
2962  const MachineInstr &TailCall) const {
2963 
2964  const MachineFunction *MF = TailCall.getMF();
2965 
2966  if (MF->getTarget().getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Kernel) {
2967  // Kernel patches thunk calls in runtime, these should never be conditional.
2968  const MachineOperand &Target = TailCall.getOperand(0);
2969  if (Target.isSymbol()) {
2970  StringRef Symbol(Target.getSymbolName());
2971  // this is currently only relevant to r11/kernel indirect thunk.
2972  if (Symbol.equals("__x86_indirect_thunk_r11"))
2973  return false;
2974  }
2975  }
2976 
2977  if (TailCall.getOpcode() != X86::TCRETURNdi &&
2978  TailCall.getOpcode() != X86::TCRETURNdi64) {
2979  // Only direct calls can be done with a conditional branch.
2980  return false;
2981  }
2982 
2983  if (Subtarget.isTargetWin64() && MF->hasWinCFI()) {
2984  // Conditional tail calls confuse the Win64 unwinder.
2985  return false;
2986  }
2987 
2988  assert(BranchCond.size() == 1);
2989  if (BranchCond[0].getImm() > X86::LAST_VALID_COND) {
2990  // Can't make a conditional tail call with this condition.
2991  return false;
2992  }
2993 
2994  const X86MachineFunctionInfo *X86FI = MF->getInfo<X86MachineFunctionInfo>();
2995  if (X86FI->getTCReturnAddrDelta() != 0 ||
2996  TailCall.getOperand(1).getImm() != 0) {
2997  // A conditional tail call cannot do any stack adjustment.
2998  return false;
2999  }
3000 
3001  return true;
3002 }
3003 
3004 void X86InstrInfo::replaceBranchWithTailCall(
3005  MachineBasicBlock &MBB, SmallVectorImpl<MachineOperand> &BranchCond,
3006  const MachineInstr &TailCall) const {
3007  assert(canMakeTailCallConditional(BranchCond, TailCall));
3008 
3009  MachineBasicBlock::iterator I = MBB.end();
3010  while (I != MBB.begin()) {
3011  --I;
3012  if (I->isDebugInstr())
3013  continue;
3014  if (!I->isBranch())
3015  assert(0 && "Can't find the branch to replace!");
3016 
3017  X86::CondCode CC = X86::getCondFromBranch(*I);
3018  assert(BranchCond.size() == 1);
3019  if (CC != BranchCond[0].getImm())
3020  continue;
3021 
3022  break;
3023  }
3024 
3025  unsigned Opc = TailCall.getOpcode() == X86::TCRETURNdi ? X86::TCRETURNdicc
3026  : X86::TCRETURNdi64cc;
3027 
3028  auto MIB = BuildMI(MBB, I, MBB.findDebugLoc(I), get(Opc));
3029  MIB->addOperand(TailCall.getOperand(0)); // Destination.
3030  MIB.addImm(0); // Stack offset (not used).
3031  MIB->addOperand(BranchCond[0]); // Condition.
3032  MIB.copyImplicitOps(TailCall); // Regmask and (imp-used) parameters.
3033 
3034  // Add implicit uses and defs of all live regs potentially clobbered by the
3035  // call. This way they still appear live across the call.
3036  LivePhysRegs LiveRegs(getRegisterInfo());
3037  LiveRegs.addLiveOuts(MBB);
3038  SmallVector<std::pair<MCPhysReg, const MachineOperand *>, 8> Clobbers;
3039  LiveRegs.stepForward(*MIB, Clobbers);
3040  for (const auto &C : Clobbers) {
3041  MIB.addReg(C.first, RegState::Implicit);
3042  MIB.addReg(C.first, RegState::Implicit | RegState::Define);
3043  }
3044 
3045  I->eraseFromParent();
3046 }
3047 
3048 // Given a MBB and its TBB, find the FBB which was a fallthrough MBB (it may
3049 // not be a fallthrough MBB now due to layout changes). Return nullptr if the
3050 // fallthrough MBB cannot be identified.
3051 static MachineBasicBlock *getFallThroughMBB(MachineBasicBlock *MBB,
3052  MachineBasicBlock *TBB) {
3053  // Look for non-EHPad successors other than TBB. If we find exactly one, it
3054  // is the fallthrough MBB. If we find zero, then TBB is both the target MBB
3055  // and fallthrough MBB. If we find more than one, we cannot identify the
3056  // fallthrough MBB and should return nullptr.
3057  MachineBasicBlock *FallthroughBB = nullptr;
3058  for (MachineBasicBlock *Succ : MBB->successors()) {
3059  if (Succ->isEHPad() || (Succ == TBB && FallthroughBB))
3060  continue;
3061  // Return a nullptr if we found more than one fallthrough successor.
3062  if (FallthroughBB && FallthroughBB != TBB)
3063  return nullptr;
3064  FallthroughBB = Succ;
3065  }
3066  return FallthroughBB;
3067 }
3068 
3069 bool X86InstrInfo::AnalyzeBranchImpl(
3070  MachineBasicBlock &MBB, MachineBasicBlock *&TBB, MachineBasicBlock *&FBB,
3071  SmallVectorImpl<MachineOperand> &Cond,
3072  SmallVectorImpl<MachineInstr *> &CondBranches, bool AllowModify) const {
3073 
3074  // Start from the bottom of the block and work up, examining the
3075  // terminator instructions.
3076  MachineBasicBlock::iterator I = MBB.end();
3077  MachineBasicBlock::iterator UnCondBrIter = MBB.end();
3078  while (I != MBB.begin()) {
3079  --I;
3080  if (I->isDebugInstr())
3081  continue;
3082 
3083  // Working from the bottom, when we see a non-terminator instruction, we're
3084  // done.
3085  if (!isUnpredicatedTerminator(*I))
3086  break;
3087 
3088  // A terminator that isn't a branch can't easily be handled by this
3089  // analysis.
3090  if (!I->isBranch())
3091  return true;
3092 
3093  // Handle unconditional branches.
3094  if (I->getOpcode() == X86::JMP_1) {
3095  UnCondBrIter = I;
3096 
3097  if (!AllowModify) {
3098  TBB = I->getOperand(0).getMBB();
3099  continue;
3100  }
3101 
3102  // If the block has any instructions after a JMP, delete them.
3103  MBB.erase(std::next(I), MBB.end());
3104 
3105  Cond.clear();
3106  FBB = nullptr;
3107 
3108  // Delete the JMP if it's equivalent to a fall-through.
3109  if (MBB.isLayoutSuccessor(I->getOperand(0).getMBB())) {
3110  TBB = nullptr;
3111  I->eraseFromParent();
3112  I = MBB.end();
3113  UnCondBrIter = MBB.end();
3114  continue;
3115  }
3116 
3117  // TBB is used to indicate the unconditional destination.
3118  TBB = I->getOperand(0).getMBB();
3119  continue;
3120  }
3121 
3122  // Handle conditional branches.
3123  X86::CondCode BranchCode = X86::getCondFromBranch(*I);
3124  if (BranchCode == X86::COND_INVALID)
3125  return true; // Can't handle indirect branch.
3126 
3127  // In practice we should never have an undef eflags operand, if we do
3128  // abort here as we are not prepared to preserve the flag.
3129  if (I->findRegisterUseOperand(X86::EFLAGS)->isUndef())
3130  return true;
3131 
3132  // Working from the bottom, handle the first conditional branch.
3133  if (Cond.empty()) {
3134  FBB = TBB;
3135  TBB = I->getOperand(0).getMBB();
3136  Cond.push_back(MachineOperand::CreateImm(BranchCode));
3137  CondBranches.push_back(&*I);
3138  continue;
3139  }
3140 
3141  // Handle subsequent conditional branches. Only handle the case where all
3142  // conditional branches branch to the same destination and their condition
3143  // opcodes fit one of the special multi-branch idioms.
3144  assert(Cond.size() == 1);
3145  assert(TBB);
3146 
3147  // If the conditions are the same, we can leave them alone.
3148  X86::CondCode OldBranchCode = (X86::CondCode)Cond[0].getImm();
3149  auto NewTBB = I->getOperand(0).getMBB();
3150  if (OldBranchCode == BranchCode && TBB == NewTBB)
3151  continue;
3152 
3153  // If they differ, see if they fit one of the known patterns. Theoretically,
3154  // we could handle more patterns here, but we shouldn't expect to see them
3155  // if instruction selection has done a reasonable job.
3156  if (TBB == NewTBB &&
3157  ((OldBranchCode == X86::COND_P && BranchCode == X86::COND_NE) ||
3158  (OldBranchCode == X86::COND_NE && BranchCode == X86::COND_P))) {
3159  BranchCode = X86::COND_NE_OR_P;
3160  } else if ((OldBranchCode == X86::COND_NP && BranchCode == X86::COND_NE) ||
3161  (OldBranchCode == X86::COND_E && BranchCode == X86::COND_P)) {
3162  if (NewTBB != (FBB ? FBB : getFallThroughMBB(&MBB, TBB)))
3163  return true;
3164 
3165  // X86::COND_E_AND_NP usually has two different branch destinations.
3166  //
3167  // JP B1
3168  // JE B2
3169  // JMP B1
3170  // B1:
3171  // B2:
3172  //
3173  // Here this condition branches to B2 only if NP && E. It has another
3174  // equivalent form:
3175  //
3176  // JNE B1
3177  // JNP B2
3178  // JMP B1
3179  // B1:
3180  // B2:
3181  //
3182  // Similarly it branches to B2 only if E && NP. That is why this condition
3183  // is named with COND_E_AND_NP.
3184  BranchCode = X86::COND_E_AND_NP;
3185  } else
3186  return true;
3187 
3188  // Update the MachineOperand.
3189  Cond[0].setImm(BranchCode);
3190  CondBranches.push_back(&*I);
3191  }
3192 
3193  return false;
3194 }
3195 
3196 bool X86InstrInfo::analyzeBranch(MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
3197  MachineBasicBlock *&TBB,
3198  MachineBasicBlock *&FBB,
3199  SmallVectorImpl<MachineOperand> &Cond,
3200  bool AllowModify) const {
3201  SmallVector<MachineInstr *, 4> CondBranches;
3202  return AnalyzeBranchImpl(MBB, TBB, FBB, Cond, CondBranches, AllowModify);
3203 }
3204 
3205 bool X86InstrInfo::analyzeBranchPredicate(MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
3206  MachineBranchPredicate &MBP,
3207  bool AllowModify) const {
3208  using namespace std::placeholders;
3209 
3210  SmallVector<MachineOperand, 4> Cond;
3211  SmallVector<MachineInstr *, 4> CondBranches;
3212  if (AnalyzeBranchImpl(MBB, MBP.TrueDest, MBP.FalseDest, Cond, CondBranches,
3213  AllowModify))
3214  return true;
3215 
3216  if (Cond.size() != 1)
3217  return true;
3218 
3219  assert(MBP.TrueDest && "expected!");
3220 
3221  if (!MBP.FalseDest)
3222  MBP.FalseDest = MBB.getNextNode();
3223 
3224  const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = &getRegisterInfo();
3225 
3226  MachineInstr *ConditionDef = nullptr;
3227  bool SingleUseCondition = true;
3228 
3229  for (MachineInstr &MI : llvm::drop_begin(llvm::reverse(MBB))) {
3230  if (MI.modifiesRegister(X86::EFLAGS, TRI)) {
3231  ConditionDef = &MI;
3232  break;
3233  }
3234 
3235  if (MI.readsRegister(X86::EFLAGS, TRI))
3236  SingleUseCondition = false;
3237  }
3238 
3239  if (!ConditionDef)
3240  return true;
3241 
3242  if (SingleUseCondition) {
3243  for (auto *Succ : MBB.successors())
3244  if (Succ->isLiveIn(X86::EFLAGS))
3245  SingleUseCondition = false;
3246  }
3247 
3248  MBP.ConditionDef = ConditionDef;
3249  MBP.SingleUseCondition = SingleUseCondition;
3250 
3251  // Currently we only recognize the simple pattern:
3252  //
3253  // test %reg, %reg
3254  // je %label
3255  //
3256  const unsigned TestOpcode =
3257  Subtarget.is64Bit() ? X86::TEST64rr : X86::TEST32rr;
3258 
3259  if (ConditionDef->getOpcode() == TestOpcode &&
3260  ConditionDef->getNumOperands() == 3 &&
3261  ConditionDef->getOperand(0).isIdenticalTo(ConditionDef->getOperand(1)) &&
3262  (Cond[0].getImm() == X86::COND_NE || Cond[0].getImm() == X86::COND_E)) {
3263  MBP.LHS = ConditionDef->getOperand(0);
3264  MBP.RHS = MachineOperand::CreateImm(0);
3265  MBP.Predicate = Cond[0].getImm() == X86::COND_NE
3266  ? MachineBranchPredicate::PRED_NE
3267  : MachineBranchPredicate::PRED_EQ;
3268  return false;
3269  }
3270 
3271  return true;
3272 }
3273 
3274 unsigned X86InstrInfo::removeBranch(MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
3275  int *BytesRemoved) const {
3276  assert(!BytesRemoved && "code size not handled");
3277 
3278  MachineBasicBlock::iterator I = MBB.end();
3279  unsigned Count = 0;
3280 
3281  while (I != MBB.begin()) {
3282  --I;
3283  if (I->isDebugInstr())
3284  continue;
3285  if (I->getOpcode() != X86::JMP_1 &&
3286  X86::getCondFromBranch(*I) == X86::COND_INVALID)
3287  break;
3288  // Remove the branch.
3289  I->eraseFromParent();
3290  I = MBB.end();
3291  ++Count;
3292  }
3293 
3294  return Count;
3295 }
3296 
3297 unsigned X86InstrInfo::insertBranch(MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
3298  MachineBasicBlock *TBB,
3299  MachineBasicBlock *FBB,
3300  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> Cond,
3301  const DebugLoc &DL,
3302  int *BytesAdded) const {
3303  // Shouldn't be a fall through.
3304  assert(TBB && "insertBranch must not be told to insert a fallthrough");
3305  assert((Cond.size() == 1 || Cond.size() == 0) &&
3306  "X86 branch conditions have one component!");
3307  assert(!BytesAdded && "code size not handled");
3308 
3309  if (Cond.empty()) {
3310  // Unconditional branch?
3311  assert(!FBB && "Unconditional branch with multiple successors!");
3312  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JMP_1)).addMBB(TBB);
3313  return 1;
3314  }
3315 
3316  // If FBB is null, it is implied to be a fall-through block.
3317  bool FallThru = FBB == nullptr;
3318 
3319  // Conditional branch.
3320  unsigned Count = 0;
3321  X86::CondCode CC = (X86::CondCode)Cond[0].getImm();
3322  switch (CC) {
3323  case X86::COND_NE_OR_P:
3324  // Synthesize NE_OR_P with two branches.
3325  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JCC_1)).addMBB(TBB).addImm(X86::COND_NE);
3326  ++Count;
3327  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JCC_1)).addMBB(TBB).addImm(X86::COND_P);
3328  ++Count;
3329  break;
3330  case X86::COND_E_AND_NP:
3331  // Use the next block of MBB as FBB if it is null.
3332  if (FBB == nullptr) {
3333  FBB = getFallThroughMBB(&MBB, TBB);
3334  assert(FBB && "MBB cannot be the last block in function when the false "
3335  "body is a fall-through.");
3336  }
3337  // Synthesize COND_E_AND_NP with two branches.
3338  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JCC_1)).addMBB(FBB).addImm(X86::COND_NE);
3339  ++Count;
3340  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JCC_1)).addMBB(TBB).addImm(X86::COND_NP);
3341  ++Count;
3342  break;
3343  default: {
3344  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JCC_1)).addMBB(TBB).addImm(CC);
3345  ++Count;
3346  }
3347  }
3348  if (!FallThru) {
3349  // Two-way Conditional branch. Insert the second branch.
3350  BuildMI(&MBB, DL, get(X86::JMP_1)).addMBB(FBB);
3351  ++Count;
3352  }
3353  return Count;
3354 }
3355 
3356 bool X86InstrInfo::canInsertSelect(const MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
3357  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> Cond,
3358  Register DstReg, Register TrueReg,
3359  Register FalseReg, int &CondCycles,
3360  int &TrueCycles, int &FalseCycles) const {
3361  // Not all subtargets have cmov instructions.
3362  if (!Subtarget.canUseCMOV())
3363  return false;
3364  if (Cond.size() != 1)
3365  return false;
3366  // We cannot do the composite conditions, at least not in SSA form.
3367  if ((X86::CondCode)Cond[0].getImm() > X86::LAST_VALID_COND)
3368  return false;
3369 
3370  // Check register classes.
3371  const MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MBB.getParent()->getRegInfo();
3372  const TargetRegisterClass *RC =
3373  RI.getCommonSubClass(MRI.getRegClass(TrueReg), MRI.getRegClass(FalseReg));
3374  if (!RC)
3375  return false;
3376 
3377  // We have cmov instructions for 16, 32, and 64 bit general purpose registers.
3378  if (X86::GR16RegClass.hasSubClassEq(RC) ||
3379  X86::GR32RegClass.hasSubClassEq(RC) ||
3380  X86::GR64RegClass.hasSubClassEq(RC)) {
3381  // This latency applies to Pentium M, Merom, Wolfdale, Nehalem, and Sandy
3382  // Bridge. Probably Ivy Bridge as well.
3383  CondCycles = 2;
3384  TrueCycles = 2;
3385  FalseCycles = 2;
3386  return true;
3387  }
3388 
3389  // Can't do vectors.
3390  return false;
3391 }
3392 
3393 void X86InstrInfo::insertSelect(MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
3394  MachineBasicBlock::iterator I,
3395  const DebugLoc &DL, Register DstReg,
3396  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> Cond, Register TrueReg,
3397  Register FalseReg) const {
3398  MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MBB.getParent()->getRegInfo();
3399  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MRI.getTargetRegisterInfo();
3400  const TargetRegisterClass &RC = *MRI.getRegClass(DstReg);
3401  assert(Cond.size() == 1 && "Invalid Cond array");
3402  unsigned Opc = X86::getCMovOpcode(TRI.getRegSizeInBits(RC) / 8,
3403  false /*HasMemoryOperand*/);
3404  BuildMI(MBB, I, DL, get(Opc), DstReg)
3405  .addReg(FalseReg)
3406  .addReg(TrueReg)
3407  .addImm(Cond[0].getImm());
3408 }
