5826 
5827 /// Inform the BreakFalseDeps pass how many idle instructions we would like
5828 /// before certain undef register reads.
5829 ///
5830 /// This catches the VCVTSI2SD family of instructions:
5831 ///
5832 /// vcvtsi2sdq %rax, undef %xmm0, %xmm14
5833 ///
5834 /// We should to be careful *not* to catch VXOR idioms which are presumably
5835 /// handled specially in the pipeline:
5836 ///
5837 /// vxorps undef %xmm1, undef %xmm1, %xmm1
5838 ///
5839 /// Like getPartialRegUpdateClearance, this makes a strong assumption that the
5840 /// high bits that are passed-through are not live.
5841 unsigned
5842 X86InstrInfo::getUndefRegClearance(const MachineInstr &MI, unsigned OpNum,
5843  const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const {
5844  const MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(OpNum);
5845  if (MO.getReg().isPhysical() && hasUndefRegUpdate(MI.getOpcode(), OpNum))
5846  return UndefRegClearance;
5847 
5848  return 0;
5849 }
5850 
5851 void X86InstrInfo::breakPartialRegDependency(
5852  MachineInstr &MI, unsigned OpNum, const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) const {
5853  Register Reg = MI.getOperand(OpNum).getReg();
5854  // If MI kills this register, the false dependence is already broken.
5855  if (MI.killsRegister(Reg, TRI))
5856  return;
5857 
5858  if (X86::VR128RegClass.contains(Reg)) {
5859  // These instructions are all floating point domain, so xorps is the best
5860  // choice.
5861  unsigned Opc = Subtarget.hasAVX() ? X86::VXORPSrr : X86::XORPSrr;
5862  BuildMI(*MI.getParent(), MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), get(Opc), Reg)
5863  .addReg(Reg, RegState::Undef)
5864  .addReg(Reg, RegState::Undef);
5865  MI.addRegisterKilled(Reg, TRI, true);
5866  } else if (X86::VR256RegClass.contains(Reg)) {
5867  // Use vxorps to clear the full ymm register.
5868  // It wants to read and write the xmm sub-register.
5869  Register XReg = TRI->getSubReg(Reg, X86::sub_xmm);
5870  BuildMI(*MI.getParent(), MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), get(X86::VXORPSrr), XReg)
5871  .addReg(XReg, RegState::Undef)
5872  .addReg(XReg, RegState::Undef)
5873  .addReg(Reg, RegState::ImplicitDefine);
5874  MI.addRegisterKilled(Reg, TRI, true);
5875  } else if (X86::VR128XRegClass.contains(Reg)) {
5876  // Only handle VLX targets.
5877  if (!Subtarget.hasVLX())
5878  return;
5879  // Since vxorps requires AVX512DQ, vpxord should be the best choice.
5880  BuildMI(*MI.getParent(), MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), get(X86::VPXORDZ128rr), Reg)
5881  .addReg(Reg, RegState::Undef)
5882  .addReg(Reg, RegState::Undef);
5883  MI.addRegisterKilled(Reg, TRI, true);
5884  } else if (X86::VR256XRegClass.contains(Reg) ||
5885  X86::VR512RegClass.contains(Reg)) {
5886  // Only handle VLX targets.
5887  if (!Subtarget.hasVLX())
5888  return;
5889  // Use vpxord to clear the full ymm/zmm register.
5890  // It wants to read and write the xmm sub-register.
5891  Register XReg = TRI->getSubReg(Reg, X86::sub_xmm);
5892  BuildMI(*MI.getParent(), MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), get(X86::VPXORDZ128rr), XReg)
5893  .addReg(XReg, RegState::Undef)
5894  .addReg(XReg, RegState::Undef)
5895  .addReg(Reg, RegState::ImplicitDefine);
5896  MI.addRegisterKilled(Reg, TRI, true);
5897  } else if (X86::GR64RegClass.contains(Reg)) {
5898  // Using XOR32rr because it has shorter encoding and zeros up the upper bits
5899  // as well.
5900  Register XReg = TRI->getSubReg(Reg, X86::sub_32bit);
5901  BuildMI(*MI.getParent(), MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), get(X86::XOR32rr), XReg)
5902  .addReg(XReg, RegState::Undef)
5903  .addReg(XReg, RegState::Undef)
5904  .addReg(Reg, RegState::ImplicitDefine);
5905  MI.addRegisterKilled(Reg, TRI, true);
5906  } else if (X86::GR32RegClass.contains(Reg)) {
5907  BuildMI(*MI.getParent(), MI, MI.getDebugLoc(), get(X86::XOR32rr), Reg)
5908  .addReg(Reg, RegState::Undef)
5909  .addReg(Reg, RegState::Undef);
5910  MI.addRegisterKilled(Reg, TRI, true);
5911  }
5912 }
5913 
5914 static void addOperands(MachineInstrBuilder &MIB, ArrayRef<MachineOperand> MOs,
5915  int PtrOffset = 0) {
5916  unsigned NumAddrOps = MOs.size();
5917 
5918  if (NumAddrOps < 4) {
5919  // FrameIndex only - add an immediate offset (whether its zero or not).
5920  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumAddrOps; ++i)
5921  MIB.add(MOs[i]);
5922  addOffset(MIB, PtrOffset);
5923  } else {
5924  // General Memory Addressing - we need to add any offset to an existing
5925  // offset.
5926  assert(MOs.size() == 5 && "Unexpected memory operand list length");
5927  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumAddrOps; ++i) {
5928  const MachineOperand &MO = MOs[i];
5929  if (i == 3 && PtrOffset != 0) {
5930  MIB.addDisp(MO, PtrOffset);
5931  } else {
5932  MIB.add(MO);
5933  }
5934  }
5935  }
5936 }
5937 
5938 static void updateOperandRegConstraints(MachineFunction &MF,
5939  MachineInstr &NewMI,
5940  const TargetInstrInfo &TII) {
5941  MachineRegisterInfo &MRI = MF.getRegInfo();
5942  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MRI.getTargetRegisterInfo();
5943 
5944  for (int Idx : llvm::seq<int>(0, NewMI.getNumOperands())) {
5945  MachineOperand &MO = NewMI.getOperand(Idx);
5946  // We only need to update constraints on virtual register operands.
5947  if (!MO.isReg())
5948  continue;
5949  Register Reg = MO.getReg();
5950  if (!Reg.isVirtual())
5951  continue;
5952 
5953  auto *NewRC = MRI.constrainRegClass(
5954  Reg, TII.getRegClass(NewMI.getDesc(), Idx, &TRI, MF));
5955  if (!NewRC) {
5956  LLVM_DEBUG(
5957  dbgs() << "WARNING: Unable to update register constraint for operand "
5958  << Idx << " of instruction:\n";
5959  NewMI.dump(); dbgs() << "\n");
5960  }
5961  }
5962 }
5963 
5964 static MachineInstr *FuseTwoAddrInst(MachineFunction &MF, unsigned Opcode,
5965  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> MOs,
5966  MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt,
5967  MachineInstr &MI,
5968  const TargetInstrInfo &TII) {
5969  // Create the base instruction with the memory operand as the first part.
5970  // Omit the implicit operands, something BuildMI can't do.
5971  MachineInstr *NewMI =
5972  MF.CreateMachineInstr(TII.get(Opcode), MI.getDebugLoc(), true);
5973  MachineInstrBuilder MIB(MF, NewMI);
5974  addOperands(MIB, MOs);
5975 
5976  // Loop over the rest of the ri operands, converting them over.
5977  unsigned NumOps = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands() - 2;
5978  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumOps; ++i) {
5979  MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(i + 2);
5980  MIB.add(MO);
5981  }
5982  for (const MachineOperand &MO : llvm::drop_begin(MI.operands(), NumOps + 2))
5983  MIB.add(MO);
5984 
5985  updateOperandRegConstraints(MF, *NewMI, TII);
5986 
5987  MachineBasicBlock *MBB = InsertPt->getParent();
5988  MBB->insert(InsertPt, NewMI);
5989 
5990  return MIB;
5991 }
5992 
5993 static MachineInstr *FuseInst(MachineFunction &MF, unsigned Opcode,
5994  unsigned OpNo, ArrayRef<MachineOperand> MOs,
5995  MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt,
5996  MachineInstr &MI, const TargetInstrInfo &TII,
5997  int PtrOffset = 0) {
5998  // Omit the implicit operands, something BuildMI can't do.
5999  MachineInstr *NewMI =
6000  MF.CreateMachineInstr(TII.get(Opcode), MI.getDebugLoc(), true);
6001  MachineInstrBuilder MIB(MF, NewMI);
6002 
6003  for (unsigned i = 0, e = MI.getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) {
6004  MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(i);
6005  if (i == OpNo) {
6006  assert(MO.isReg() && "Expected to fold into reg operand!");
6007  addOperands(MIB, MOs, PtrOffset);
6008  } else {
6009  MIB.add(MO);
6010  }
6011  }
6012 
6013  updateOperandRegConstraints(MF, *NewMI, TII);
6014 
6015  // Copy the NoFPExcept flag from the instruction we're fusing.
6016  if (MI.getFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoFPExcept))
6017  NewMI->setFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoFPExcept);
6018 
6019  MachineBasicBlock *MBB = InsertPt->getParent();
6020  MBB->insert(InsertPt, NewMI);
6021 
6022  return MIB;
6023 }
6024 
6025 static MachineInstr *MakeM0Inst(const TargetInstrInfo &TII, unsigned Opcode,
6026  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> MOs,
6027  MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt,
6028  MachineInstr &MI) {
6029  MachineInstrBuilder MIB = BuildMI(*InsertPt->getParent(), InsertPt,
6030  MI.getDebugLoc(), TII.get(Opcode));
6031  addOperands(MIB, MOs);
6032  return MIB.addImm(0);
6033 }
6034 
6035 MachineInstr *X86InstrInfo::foldMemoryOperandCustom(
6036  MachineFunction &MF, MachineInstr &MI, unsigned OpNum,
6037  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> MOs, MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt,
6038  unsigned Size, Align Alignment) const {
6039  switch (MI.getOpcode()) {
6040  case X86::INSERTPSrr:
6041  case X86::VINSERTPSrr:
6042  case X86::VINSERTPSZrr:
6043  // Attempt to convert the load of inserted vector into a fold load
6044  // of a single float.
6045  if (OpNum == 2) {
6046  unsigned Imm = MI.getOperand(MI.getNumOperands() - 1).getImm();
6047  unsigned ZMask = Imm & 15;
6048  unsigned DstIdx = (Imm >> 4) & 3;
6049  unsigned SrcIdx = (Imm >> 6) & 3;
6050 
6051  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
6052  const TargetRegisterClass *RC = getRegClass(MI.getDesc(), OpNum, &RI, MF);
6053  unsigned RCSize = TRI.getRegSizeInBits(*RC) / 8;
6054  if ((Size == 0 || Size >= 16) && RCSize >= 16 && Alignment >= Align(4)) {
6055  int PtrOffset = SrcIdx * 4;
6056  unsigned NewImm = (DstIdx << 4) | ZMask;
6057  unsigned NewOpCode =
6058  (MI.getOpcode() == X86::VINSERTPSZrr) ? X86::VINSERTPSZrm :
6059  (MI.getOpcode() == X86::VINSERTPSrr) ? X86::VINSERTPSrm :
6060  X86::INSERTPSrm;
6061  MachineInstr *NewMI =
6062  FuseInst(MF, NewOpCode, OpNum, MOs, InsertPt, MI, *this, PtrOffset);
6063  NewMI->getOperand(NewMI->getNumOperands() - 1).setImm(NewImm);
6064  return NewMI;
6065  }
6066  }
6067  break;
6068  case X86::MOVHLPSrr:
6069  case X86::VMOVHLPSrr:
6070  case X86::VMOVHLPSZrr:
6071  // Move the upper 64-bits of the second operand to the lower 64-bits.
6072  // To fold the load, adjust the pointer to the upper and use (V)MOVLPS.
6073  // TODO: In most cases AVX doesn't have a 8-byte alignment requirement.
6074  if (OpNum == 2) {
6075  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
6076  const TargetRegisterClass *RC = getRegClass(MI.getDesc(), OpNum, &RI, MF);
6077  unsigned RCSize = TRI.getRegSizeInBits(*RC) / 8;
6078  if ((Size == 0 || Size >= 16) && RCSize >= 16 && Alignment >= Align(8)) {
6079  unsigned NewOpCode =
6080  (MI.getOpcode() == X86::VMOVHLPSZrr) ? X86::VMOVLPSZ128rm :
6081  (MI.getOpcode() == X86::VMOVHLPSrr) ? X86::VMOVLPSrm :
6082  X86::MOVLPSrm;
6083  MachineInstr *NewMI =
6084  FuseInst(MF, NewOpCode, OpNum, MOs, InsertPt, MI, *this, 8);
6085  return NewMI;
6086  }
6087  }
6088  break;
6089  case X86::UNPCKLPDrr:
6090  // If we won't be able to fold this to the memory form of UNPCKL, use
6091  // MOVHPD instead. Done as custom because we can't have this in the load
6092  // table twice.
6093  if (OpNum == 2) {
6094  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
6095  const TargetRegisterClass *RC = getRegClass(MI.getDesc(), OpNum, &RI, MF);
6096  unsigned RCSize = TRI.getRegSizeInBits(*RC) / 8;
6097  if ((Size == 0 || Size >= 16) && RCSize >= 16 && Alignment < Align(16)) {
6098  MachineInstr *NewMI =
6099  FuseInst(MF, X86::MOVHPDrm, OpNum, MOs, InsertPt, MI, *this);
6100  return NewMI;
6101  }
6102  }
6103  break;
6104  }
6105 
6106  return nullptr;
6107 }
6108 
6109 static bool shouldPreventUndefRegUpdateMemFold(MachineFunction &MF,
6110  MachineInstr &MI) {
6111  if (!hasUndefRegUpdate(MI.getOpcode(), 1, /*ForLoadFold*/true) ||
6112  !MI.getOperand(1).isReg())
6113  return false;
6114 
6115  // The are two cases we need to handle depending on where in the pipeline
6116  // the folding attempt is being made.
6117  // -Register has the undef flag set.
6118  // -Register is produced by the IMPLICIT_DEF instruction.
6119 
6120  if (MI.getOperand(1).isUndef())
6121  return true;
6122 
6123  MachineRegisterInfo &RegInfo = MF.getRegInfo();
6124  MachineInstr *VRegDef = RegInfo.getUniqueVRegDef(MI.getOperand(1).getReg());
6125  return VRegDef && VRegDef->isImplicitDef();
6126 }
6127 
6128 MachineInstr *X86InstrInfo::foldMemoryOperandImpl(
6129  MachineFunction &MF, MachineInstr &MI, unsigned OpNum,
6130  ArrayRef<MachineOperand> MOs, MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt,
6131  unsigned Size, Align Alignment, bool AllowCommute) const {
6132  bool isSlowTwoMemOps = Subtarget.slowTwoMemOps();
6133  bool isTwoAddrFold = false;
6134 
6135  // For CPUs that favor the register form of a call or push,
6136  // do not fold loads into calls or pushes, unless optimizing for size
6137  // aggressively.
6138  if (isSlowTwoMemOps && !MF.getFunction().hasMinSize() &&
6139  (MI.getOpcode() == X86::CALL32r || MI.getOpcode() == X86::CALL64r ||
6140  MI.getOpcode() == X86::PUSH16r || MI.getOpcode() == X86::PUSH32r ||
6141  MI.getOpcode() == X86::PUSH64r))
6142  return nullptr;
6143 
6144  // Avoid partial and undef register update stalls unless optimizing for size.
6145  if (!MF.getFunction().hasOptSize() &&
6146  (hasPartialRegUpdate(MI.getOpcode(), Subtarget, /*ForLoadFold*/true) ||
6147  shouldPreventUndefRegUpdateMemFold(MF, MI)))
6148  return nullptr;
6149 
6150  unsigned NumOps = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands();
6151  bool isTwoAddr =
6152  NumOps > 1 && MI.getDesc().getOperandConstraint(1, MCOI::TIED_TO) != -1;
6153 
6154  // FIXME: AsmPrinter doesn't know how to handle
6155  // X86II::MO_GOT_ABSOLUTE_ADDRESS after folding.
6156  if (MI.getOpcode() == X86::ADD32ri &&
6157  MI.getOperand(2).getTargetFlags() == X86II::MO_GOT_ABSOLUTE_ADDRESS)
6158  return nullptr;
6159 
6160  // GOTTPOFF relocation loads can only be folded into add instructions.
6161  // FIXME: Need to exclude other relocations that only support specific
6162  // instructions.
6163  if (MOs.size() == X86::AddrNumOperands &&
6164  MOs[X86::AddrDisp].getTargetFlags() == X86II::MO_GOTTPOFF &&
6165  MI.getOpcode() != X86::ADD64rr)
6166  return nullptr;
6167 
6168  // Don't fold loads into indirect calls that need a KCFI check as we'll
6169  // have to unfold these in X86KCFIPass anyway.
6170  if (MI.isCall() && MI.getCFIType())
6171  return nullptr;
6172 
6173  MachineInstr *NewMI = nullptr;
6174 
6175  // Attempt to fold any custom cases we have.
6176  if (MachineInstr *CustomMI = foldMemoryOperandCustom(
6177  MF, MI, OpNum, MOs, InsertPt, Size, Alignment))
6178  return CustomMI;
6179 
6180  const X86MemoryFoldTableEntry *I = nullptr;
6181 
6182  // Folding a memory location into the two-address part of a two-address
6183  // instruction is different than folding it other places. It requires
6184  // replacing the *two* registers with the memory location.
6185  if (isTwoAddr && NumOps >= 2 && OpNum < 2 && MI.getOperand(0).isReg() &&
6186  MI.getOperand(1).isReg() &&
6187  MI.getOperand(0).getReg() == MI.getOperand(1).getReg()) {
6188  I = lookupTwoAddrFoldTable(MI.getOpcode());
6189  isTwoAddrFold = true;
6190  } else {
6191  if (OpNum == 0) {
6192  if (MI.getOpcode() == X86::MOV32r0) {
6193  NewMI = MakeM0Inst(*this, X86::MOV32mi, MOs, InsertPt, MI);
6194  if (NewMI)
6195  return NewMI;
6196  }
6197  }
6198 
6199  I = lookupFoldTable(MI.getOpcode(), OpNum);
6200  }
6201 
6202  if (I != nullptr) {
6203  unsigned Opcode = I->DstOp;
6204  bool FoldedLoad =
6205  isTwoAddrFold || (OpNum == 0 && I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_LOAD) || OpNum > 0;
6206  bool FoldedStore =
6207  isTwoAddrFold || (OpNum == 0 && I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_STORE);
6208  MaybeAlign MinAlign =
6209  decodeMaybeAlign((I->Flags & TB_ALIGN_MASK) >> TB_ALIGN_SHIFT);
6210  if (MinAlign && Alignment < *MinAlign)
6211  return nullptr;
6212  bool NarrowToMOV32rm = false;
6213  if (Size) {
6214  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
6215  const TargetRegisterClass *RC = getRegClass(MI.getDesc(), OpNum,
6216  &RI, MF);
6217  unsigned RCSize = TRI.getRegSizeInBits(*RC) / 8;
6218  // Check if it's safe to fold the load. If the size of the object is
6219  // narrower than the load width, then it's not.
6220  // FIXME: Allow scalar intrinsic instructions like ADDSSrm_Int.
6221  if (FoldedLoad && Size < RCSize) {
6222  // If this is a 64-bit load, but the spill slot is 32, then we can do
6223  // a 32-bit load which is implicitly zero-extended. This likely is
6224  // due to live interval analysis remat'ing a load from stack slot.
6225  if (Opcode != X86::MOV64rm || RCSize != 8 || Size != 4)
6226  return nullptr;
6227  if (MI.getOperand(0).getSubReg() || MI.getOperand(1).getSubReg())
6228  return nullptr;
6229  Opcode = X86::MOV32rm;
6230  NarrowToMOV32rm = true;
6231  }
6232  // For stores, make sure the size of the object is equal to the size of
6233  // the store. If the object is larger, the extra bits would be garbage. If
6234  // the object is smaller we might overwrite another object or fault.
6235  if (FoldedStore && Size != RCSize)
6236  return nullptr;
6237  }
6238 
6239  if (isTwoAddrFold)
6240  NewMI = FuseTwoAddrInst(MF, Opcode, MOs, InsertPt, MI, *this);
6241  else
6242  NewMI = FuseInst(MF, Opcode, OpNum, MOs, InsertPt, MI, *this);
6243 
6244  if (NarrowToMOV32rm) {
6245  // If this is the special case where we use a MOV32rm to load a 32-bit
6246  // value and zero-extend the top bits. Change the destination register
6247  // to a 32-bit one.
6248  Register DstReg = NewMI->getOperand(0).getReg();
6249  if (DstReg.isPhysical())
6250  NewMI->getOperand(0).setReg(RI.getSubReg(DstReg, X86::sub_32bit));
6251  else
6252  NewMI->getOperand(0).setSubReg(X86::sub_32bit);
6253  }
6254  return NewMI;
6255  }
6256 
6257  // If the instruction and target operand are commutable, commute the
6258  // instruction and try again.
6259  if (AllowCommute) {
6260  unsigned CommuteOpIdx1 = OpNum, CommuteOpIdx2 = CommuteAnyOperandIndex;
6261  if (findCommutedOpIndices(MI, CommuteOpIdx1, CommuteOpIdx2)) {
6262  bool HasDef = MI.getDesc().getNumDefs();
6263  Register Reg0 = HasDef ? MI.getOperand(0).getReg() : Register();
6264  Register Reg1 = MI.getOperand(CommuteOpIdx1).getReg();
6265  Register Reg2 = MI.getOperand(CommuteOpIdx2).getReg();
6266  bool Tied1 =
6267  0 == MI.getDesc().getOperandConstraint(CommuteOpIdx1, MCOI::TIED_TO);
6268  bool Tied2 =
6269  0 == MI.getDesc().getOperandConstraint(CommuteOpIdx2, MCOI::TIED_TO);
6270 
6271  // If either of the commutable operands are tied to the destination
6272  // then we can not commute + fold.
6273  if ((HasDef && Reg0 == Reg1 && Tied1) ||
6274  (HasDef && Reg0 == Reg2 && Tied2))
6275  return nullptr;
6276 
6277  MachineInstr *CommutedMI =
6278  commuteInstruction(MI, false, CommuteOpIdx1, CommuteOpIdx2);
6279  if (!CommutedMI) {
6280  // Unable to commute.
6281  return nullptr;
6282  }
6283  if (CommutedMI != &MI) {
6284  // New instruction. We can't fold from this.
6285  CommutedMI->eraseFromParent();
6286  return nullptr;
6287  }
6288 
6289  // Attempt to fold with the commuted version of the instruction.
6290  NewMI = foldMemoryOperandImpl(MF, MI, CommuteOpIdx2, MOs, InsertPt, Size,
6291  Alignment, /*AllowCommute=*/false);
6292  if (NewMI)
6293  return NewMI;
6294 
6295  // Folding failed again - undo the commute before returning.
6296  MachineInstr *UncommutedMI =
6297  commuteInstruction(MI, false, CommuteOpIdx1, CommuteOpIdx2);
6298  if (!UncommutedMI) {
6299  // Unable to commute.
6300  return nullptr;
6301  }
6302  if (UncommutedMI != &MI) {
6303  // New instruction. It doesn't need to be kept.
6304  UncommutedMI->eraseFromParent();
6305  return nullptr;
6306  }
6307 
6308  // Return here to prevent duplicate fuse failure report.
6309  return nullptr;
6310  }
6311  }
6312 
6313  // No fusion
6314  if (PrintFailedFusing && !MI.isCopy())
6315  dbgs() << "We failed to fuse operand " << OpNum << " in " << MI;
6316  return nullptr;
6317 }
6318 
6319 MachineInstr *
6320 X86InstrInfo::foldMemoryOperandImpl(MachineFunction &MF, MachineInstr &MI,
6321  ArrayRef<unsigned> Ops,
6322  MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt,
6323  int FrameIndex, LiveIntervals *LIS,
6324  VirtRegMap *VRM) const {
6325  // Check switch flag
6326  if (NoFusing)
6327  return nullptr;
6328 
6329  // Avoid partial and undef register update stalls unless optimizing for size.
6330  if (!MF.getFunction().hasOptSize() &&
6331  (hasPartialRegUpdate(MI.getOpcode(), Subtarget, /*ForLoadFold*/true) ||
6332  shouldPreventUndefRegUpdateMemFold(MF, MI)))
6333  return nullptr;
6334 
6335  // Don't fold subreg spills, or reloads that use a high subreg.
6336  for (auto Op : Ops) {
6337  MachineOperand &MO = MI.getOperand(Op);
6338  auto SubReg = MO.getSubReg();
6339  if (SubReg && (MO.isDef() || SubReg == X86::sub_8bit_hi))
6340  return nullptr;
6341  }
6342 
6343  const MachineFrameInfo &MFI = MF.getFrameInfo();
6344  unsigned Size = MFI.getObjectSize(FrameIndex);
6345  Align Alignment = MFI.getObjectAlign(FrameIndex);
6346  // If the function stack isn't realigned we don't want to fold instructions
6347  // that need increased alignment.
6348  if (!RI.hasStackRealignment(MF))
6349  Alignment =
6350  std::min(Alignment, Subtarget.getFrameLowering()->getStackAlign());
6351  if (Ops.size() == 2 && Ops[0] == 0 && Ops[1] == 1) {
6352  unsigned NewOpc = 0;
6353  unsigned RCSize = 0;
6354  switch (MI.getOpcode()) {
6355  default: return nullptr;
6356  case X86::TEST8rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP8ri; RCSize = 1; break;
6357  case X86::TEST16rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP16ri8; RCSize = 2; break;
6358  case X86::TEST32rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP32ri8; RCSize = 4; break;
6359  case X86::TEST64rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP64ri8; RCSize = 8; break;
6360  }
6361  // Check if it's safe to fold the load. If the size of the object is
6362  // narrower than the load width, then it's not.
6363  if (Size < RCSize)
6364  return nullptr;
6365  // Change to CMPXXri r, 0 first.
6366  MI.setDesc(get(NewOpc));
6367  MI.getOperand(1).ChangeToImmediate(0);
6368  } else if (Ops.size() != 1)
6369  return nullptr;
6370 
6371  return foldMemoryOperandImpl(MF, MI, Ops[0],
6372  MachineOperand::CreateFI(FrameIndex), InsertPt,
6373  Size, Alignment, /*AllowCommute=*/true);
6374 }
6375 
6376 /// Check if \p LoadMI is a partial register load that we can't fold into \p MI
6377 /// because the latter uses contents that wouldn't be defined in the folded
6378 /// version. For instance, this transformation isn't legal:
6379 /// movss (%rdi), %xmm0
6380 /// addps %xmm0, %xmm0
6381 /// ->
6382 /// addps (%rdi), %xmm0
6383 ///
6384 /// But this one is:
6385 /// movss (%rdi), %xmm0
6386 /// addss %xmm0, %xmm0
6387 /// ->
6388 /// addss (%rdi), %xmm0
6389 ///
6390 static bool isNonFoldablePartialRegisterLoad(const MachineInstr &LoadMI,
6391  const MachineInstr &UserMI,
6392  const MachineFunction &MF) {
6393  unsigned Opc = LoadMI.getOpcode();
6394  unsigned UserOpc = UserMI.getOpcode();
6395  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
6396  const TargetRegisterClass *RC =
6397  MF.getRegInfo().getRegClass(LoadMI.getOperand(0).getReg());
6398  unsigned RegSize = TRI.getRegSizeInBits(*RC);
6399 
6400  if ((Opc == X86::MOVSSrm || Opc == X86::VMOVSSrm || Opc == X86::VMOVSSZrm ||
6401  Opc == X86::MOVSSrm_alt || Opc == X86::VMOVSSrm_alt ||
6402  Opc == X86::VMOVSSZrm_alt) &&
6403  RegSize > 32) {
6404  // These instructions only load 32 bits, we can't fold them if the
6405  // destination register is wider than 32 bits (4 bytes), and its user
6406  // instruction isn't scalar (SS).
6407  switch (UserOpc) {
6408  case X86::CVTSS2SDrr_Int:
6409  case X86::VCVTSS2SDrr_Int:
6410  case X86::VCVTSS2SDZrr_Int:
6411  case X86::VCVTSS2SDZrr_Intk:
6412  case X86::VCVTSS2SDZrr_Intkz:
6413  case X86::CVTSS2SIrr_Int: case X86::CVTSS2SI64rr_Int:
6414  case X86::VCVTSS2SIrr_Int: case X86::VCVTSS2SI64rr_Int:
6415  case X86::VCVTSS2SIZrr_Int: case X86::VCVTSS2SI64Zrr_Int:
6416  case X86::CVTTSS2SIrr_Int: case X86::CVTTSS2SI64rr_Int:
6417  case X86::VCVTTSS2SIrr_Int: case X86::VCVTTSS2SI64rr_Int:
6418  case X86::VCVTTSS2SIZrr_Int: case X86::VCVTTSS2SI64Zrr_Int:
6419  case X86::VCVTSS2USIZrr_Int: case X86::VCVTSS2USI64Zrr_Int:
6420  case X86::VCVTTSS2USIZrr_Int: case X86::VCVTTSS2USI64Zrr_Int:
6421  case X86::RCPSSr_Int: case X86::VRCPSSr_Int:

6573  case X86::VFMSUB213SDZr_Intkz: case X86::VFNMSUB213SDZr_Intkz:
6574  case X86::VFMSUB231SDZr_Intkz: case X86::VFNMSUB231SDZr_Intkz:
6575  case X86::VFIXUPIMMSDZrri:
6576  case X86::VFIXUPIMMSDZrrik:
6577  case X86::VFIXUPIMMSDZrrikz:
6578  case X86::VFPCLASSSDZrr:
6579  case X86::VFPCLASSSDZrrk:
6580  case X86::VGETEXPSDZr:
6581  case X86::VGETEXPSDZrk:
6582  case X86::VGETEXPSDZrkz:
6583  case X86::VGETMANTSDZrri:
6584  case X86::VGETMANTSDZrrik:
6585  case X86::VGETMANTSDZrrikz:
6586  case X86::VRANGESDZrri:
6587  case X86::VRANGESDZrrik:
6588  case X86::VRANGESDZrrikz:
6589  case X86::VRCP14SDZrr:
6590  case X86::VRCP14SDZrrk:
6591  case X86::VRCP14SDZrrkz:
6592  case X86::VRCP28SDZr:

6598  case X86::VRNDSCALESDZr_Int:
6599  case X86::VRNDSCALESDZr_Intk:
6600  case X86::VRNDSCALESDZr_Intkz:
6601  case X86::VRSQRT14SDZrr:
6602  case X86::VRSQRT14SDZrrk:
6603  case X86::VRSQRT14SDZrrkz:
6604  case X86::VRSQRT28SDZr:
6605  case X86::VRSQRT28SDZrk:

6611  default:

6613  }
6614  }
6615 
6616  if ((Opc == X86::VMOVSHZrm || Opc == X86::VMOVSHZrm_alt) && RegSize > 16) {
6617  // These instructions only load 16 bits, we can't fold them if the
6618  // destination register is wider than 16 bits (2 bytes), and its user
6619  // instruction isn't scalar (SH).
6620  switch (UserOpc) {
6621  case X86::VADDSHZrr_Int:
6622  case X86::VCMPSHZrr_Int:
6623  case X86::VDIVSHZrr_Int:
6624  case X86::VMAXSHZrr_Int:
6625  case X86::VMINSHZrr_Int:
6626  case X86::VMULSHZrr_Int:
6627  case X86::VSUBSHZrr_Int:
6628  case X86::VADDSHZrr_Intk: case X86::VADDSHZrr_Intkz:
6629  case X86::VCMPSHZrr_Intk:
6630  case X86::VDIVSHZrr_Intk: case X86::VDIVSHZrr_Intkz:
6631  case X86::VMAXSHZrr_Intk: case X86::VMAXSHZrr_Intkz:
6632  case X86::VMINSHZrr_Intk: case X86::VMINSHZrr_Intkz:
6633  case X86::VMULSHZrr_Intk: case X86::VMULSHZrr_Intkz:
6634  case X86::VSUBSHZrr_Intk: case X86::VSUBSHZrr_Intkz:
6635  case X86::VFMADD132SHZr_Int: case X86::VFNMADD132SHZr_Int:
6636  case X86::VFMADD213SHZr_Int: case X86::VFNMADD213SHZr_Int:
6637  case X86::VFMADD231SHZr_Int: case X86::VFNMADD231SHZr_Int:
6638  case X86::VFMSUB132SHZr_Int: case X86::VFNMSUB132SHZr_Int:

6640  case X86::VFMSUB231SHZr_Int: case X86::VFNMSUB231SHZr_Int:
6641  case X86::VFMADD132SHZr_Intk: case X86::VFNMADD132SHZr_Intk:
6642  case X86::VFMADD213SHZr_Intk: case X86::VFNMADD213SHZr_Intk:
6643  case X86::VFMADD231SHZr_Intk: case X86::VFNMADD231SHZr_Intk:

6650  case X86::VFMSUB132SHZr_Intkz: case X86::VFNMSUB132SHZr_Intkz:
6651  case X86::VFMSUB213SHZr_Intkz: case X86::VFNMSUB213SHZr_Intkz:

6656  }
6657  }
6658 
6659  return false;
6660 }
6661 
6662 MachineInstr *X86InstrInfo::foldMemoryOperandImpl(
6663  MachineFunction &MF, MachineInstr &MI, ArrayRef<unsigned> Ops,
6664  MachineBasicBlock::iterator InsertPt, MachineInstr &LoadMI,
6665  LiveIntervals *LIS) const {
6666 
6667  // TODO: Support the case where LoadMI loads a wide register, but MI
6668  // only uses a subreg.
6669  for (auto Op : Ops) {
6670  if (MI.getOperand(Op).getSubReg())
6671  return nullptr;
6672  }
6673 
6674  // If loading from a FrameIndex, fold directly from the FrameIndex.
6675  unsigned NumOps = LoadMI.getDesc().getNumOperands();
6676  int FrameIndex;
6677  if (isLoadFromStackSlot(LoadMI, FrameIndex)) {
6678  if (isNonFoldablePartialRegisterLoad(LoadMI, MI, MF))
6679  return nullptr;
6680  return foldMemoryOperandImpl(MF, MI, Ops, InsertPt, FrameIndex, LIS);
6681  }
6682 
6683  // Check switch flag
6684  if (NoFusing) return nullptr;
6685 
6686  // Avoid partial and undef register update stalls unless optimizing for size.
6687  if (!MF.getFunction().hasOptSize() &&
6688  (hasPartialRegUpdate(MI.getOpcode(), Subtarget, /*ForLoadFold*/true) ||
6689  shouldPreventUndefRegUpdateMemFold(MF, MI)))
6690  return nullptr;
6691 
6692  // Determine the alignment of the load.
6693  Align Alignment;
6694  if (LoadMI.hasOneMemOperand())
6695  Alignment = (*LoadMI.memoperands_begin())->getAlign();
6696  else
6697  switch (LoadMI.getOpcode()) {
6698  case X86::AVX512_512_SET0:
6699  case X86::AVX512_512_SETALLONES:
6700  Alignment = Align(64);
6701  break;
6702  case X86::AVX2_SETALLONES:
6703  case X86::AVX1_SETALLONES:
6704  case X86::AVX_SET0:
6705  case X86::AVX512_256_SET0:
6706  Alignment = Align(32);
6707  break;
6708  case X86::V_SET0:
6709  case X86::V_SETALLONES:
6710  case X86::AVX512_128_SET0:
6711  case X86::FsFLD0F128:
6712  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0F128:
6713  Alignment = Align(16);
6714  break;
6715  case X86::MMX_SET0:
6716  case X86::FsFLD0SD:
6717  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SD:
6718  Alignment = Align(8);
6719  break;
6720  case X86::FsFLD0SS:
6721  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SS:
6722  Alignment = Align(4);
6723  break;
6724  case X86::FsFLD0SH:
6725  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SH:
6726  Alignment = Align(2);
6727  break;
6728  default:
6729  return nullptr;
6730  }
6731  if (Ops.size() == 2 && Ops[0] == 0 && Ops[1] == 1) {
6732  unsigned NewOpc = 0;
6733  switch (MI.getOpcode()) {
6734  default: return nullptr;
6735  case X86::TEST8rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP8ri; break;
6736  case X86::TEST16rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP16ri8; break;
6737  case X86::TEST32rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP32ri8; break;
6738  case X86::TEST64rr: NewOpc = X86::CMP64ri8; break;
6739  }
6740  // Change to CMPXXri r, 0 first.
6741  MI.setDesc(get(NewOpc));
6742  MI.getOperand(1).ChangeToImmediate(0);
6743  } else if (Ops.size() != 1)
6744  return nullptr;
6745 
6746  // Make sure the subregisters match.
6747  // Otherwise we risk changing the size of the load.
6748  if (LoadMI.getOperand(0).getSubReg() != MI.getOperand(Ops[0]).getSubReg())
6749  return nullptr;
6750 
6751  SmallVector<MachineOperand,X86::AddrNumOperands> MOs;
6752  switch (LoadMI.getOpcode()) {
6753  case X86::MMX_SET0:
6754  case X86::V_SET0:
6755  case X86::V_SETALLONES:
6756  case X86::AVX2_SETALLONES:
6757  case X86::AVX1_SETALLONES:
6758  case X86::AVX_SET0:
6759  case X86::AVX512_128_SET0:
6760  case X86::AVX512_256_SET0:
6761  case X86::AVX512_512_SET0:
6762  case X86::AVX512_512_SETALLONES:
6763  case X86::FsFLD0SH:
6764  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SH:
6765  case X86::FsFLD0SD:
6766  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SD:
6767  case X86::FsFLD0SS:
6768  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SS:
6769  case X86::FsFLD0F128:
6770  case X86::AVX512_FsFLD0F128: {
6771  // Folding a V_SET0 or V_SETALLONES as a load, to ease register pressure.
6772  // Create a constant-pool entry and operands to load from it.
6773 
6774  // Medium and large mode can't fold loads this way.
6775  if (MF.getTarget().getCodeModel() != CodeModel::Small &&
6776  MF.getTarget().getCodeModel() != CodeModel::Kernel)
6777  return nullptr;
6778 
6779  // x86-32 PIC requires a PIC base register for constant pools.
6780  unsigned PICBase = 0;
6781  // Since we're using Small or Kernel code model, we can always use
6782  // RIP-relative addressing for a smaller encoding.
6783  if (Subtarget.is64Bit()) {
6784  PICBase = X86::RIP;
6785  } else if (MF.getTarget().isPositionIndependent()) {
6786  // FIXME: PICBase = getGlobalBaseReg(&MF);
6787  // This doesn't work for several reasons.
6788  // 1. GlobalBaseReg may have been spilled.
6789  // 2. It may not be live at MI.
6790  return nullptr;
6791  }
6792 
6793  // Create a constant-pool entry.
6794  MachineConstantPool &MCP = *MF.getConstantPool();
6795  Type *Ty;
6796  unsigned Opc = LoadMI.getOpcode();
6797  if (Opc == X86::FsFLD0SS || Opc == X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SS)
6798  Ty = Type::getFloatTy(MF.getFunction().getContext());
6799  else if (Opc == X86::FsFLD0SD || Opc == X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SD)
6800  Ty = Type::getDoubleTy(MF.getFunction().getContext());
6801  else if (Opc == X86::FsFLD0F128 || Opc == X86::AVX512_FsFLD0F128)
6802  Ty = Type::getFP128Ty(MF.getFunction().getContext());
6803  else if (Opc == X86::FsFLD0SH || Opc == X86::AVX512_FsFLD0SH)
6804  Ty = Type::getHalfTy(MF.getFunction().getContext());
6805  else if (Opc == X86::AVX512_512_SET0 || Opc == X86::AVX512_512_SETALLONES)
6806  Ty = FixedVectorType::get(Type::getInt32Ty(MF.getFunction().getContext()),
6807  16);
6808  else if (Opc == X86::AVX2_SETALLONES || Opc == X86::AVX_SET0 ||
6809  Opc == X86::AVX512_256_SET0 || Opc == X86::AVX1_SETALLONES)
6810  Ty = FixedVectorType::get(Type::getInt32Ty(MF.getFunction().getContext()),
6811  8);
6812  else if (Opc == X86::MMX_SET0)
6813  Ty = FixedVectorType::get(Type::getInt32Ty(MF.getFunction().getContext()),
6814  2);
6815  else
6816  Ty = FixedVectorType::get(Type::getInt32Ty(MF.getFunction().getContext()),
6817  4);
6818 
6819  bool IsAllOnes = (Opc == X86::V_SETALLONES || Opc == X86::AVX2_SETALLONES ||
6820  Opc == X86::AVX512_512_SETALLONES ||
6821  Opc == X86::AVX1_SETALLONES);
6822  const Constant *C = IsAllOnes ? Constant::getAllOnesValue(Ty) :
6823  Constant::getNullValue(Ty);
6824  unsigned CPI = MCP.getConstantPoolIndex(C, Alignment);
6825 
6826  // Create operands to load from the constant pool entry.
6827  MOs.push_back(MachineOperand::CreateReg(PICBase, false));
6828  MOs.push_back(MachineOperand::CreateImm(1));
6829  MOs.push_back(MachineOperand::CreateReg(0, false));
6830  MOs.push_back(MachineOperand::CreateCPI(CPI, 0));
6831  MOs.push_back(MachineOperand::CreateReg(0, false));
6832  break;
6833  }
6834  default: {
6835  if (isNonFoldablePartialRegisterLoad(LoadMI, MI, MF))
6836  return nullptr;
6837 
6838  // Folding a normal load. Just copy the load's address operands.
6839  MOs.append(LoadMI.operands_begin() + NumOps - X86::AddrNumOperands,
6840  LoadMI.operands_begin() + NumOps);
6841  break;
6842  }
6843  }
6844  return foldMemoryOperandImpl(MF, MI, Ops[0], MOs, InsertPt,
6845  /*Size=*/0, Alignment, /*AllowCommute=*/true);
6846 }
6847 
6848 static SmallVector<MachineMemOperand *, 2>
6849 extractLoadMMOs(ArrayRef<MachineMemOperand *> MMOs, MachineFunction &MF) {
6850  SmallVector<MachineMemOperand *, 2> LoadMMOs;
6851 
6852  for (MachineMemOperand *MMO : MMOs) {
6853  if (!MMO->isLoad())
6854  continue;
6855 
6856  if (!MMO->isStore()) {
6857  // Reuse the MMO.
6858  LoadMMOs.push_back(MMO);
6859  } else {
6860  // Clone the MMO and unset the store flag.
6861  LoadMMOs.push_back(MF.getMachineMemOperand(
6862  MMO, MMO->getFlags() & ~MachineMemOperand::MOStore));
6863  }
6864  }
6865 
6866  return LoadMMOs;
6867 }
6868 
6869 static SmallVector<MachineMemOperand *, 2>
6870 extractStoreMMOs(ArrayRef<MachineMemOperand *> MMOs, MachineFunction &MF) {
6871  SmallVector<MachineMemOperand *, 2> StoreMMOs;
6872 
6873  for (MachineMemOperand *MMO : MMOs) {
6874  if (!MMO->isStore())
6875  continue;
6876 
6877  if (!MMO->isLoad()) {
6878  // Reuse the MMO.
6879  StoreMMOs.push_back(MMO);
6880  } else {
6881  // Clone the MMO and unset the load flag.
6882  StoreMMOs.push_back(MF.getMachineMemOperand(
6883  MMO, MMO->getFlags() & ~MachineMemOperand::MOLoad));
6884  }
6885  }
6886 
6887  return StoreMMOs;
6888 }
6889 
6890 static unsigned getBroadcastOpcode(const X86MemoryFoldTableEntry *I,
6891  const TargetRegisterClass *RC,
6892  const X86Subtarget &STI) {
6893  assert(STI.hasAVX512() && "Expected at least AVX512!");
6894  unsigned SpillSize = STI.getRegisterInfo()->getSpillSize(*RC);
6895  assert((SpillSize == 64 || STI.hasVLX()) &&
6896  "Can't broadcast less than 64 bytes without AVX512VL!");
6897 
6898  switch (I->Flags & TB_BCAST_MASK) {
6899  default: llvm_unreachable("Unexpected broadcast type!");
6900  case TB_BCAST_D:
6901  switch (SpillSize) {
6902  default: llvm_unreachable("Unknown spill size");
6903  case 16: return X86::VPBROADCASTDZ128rm;
6904  case 32: return X86::VPBROADCASTDZ256rm;
6905  case 64: return X86::VPBROADCASTDZrm;
6906  }
6907  break;
6908  case TB_BCAST_Q:
6909  switch (SpillSize) {
6910  default: llvm_unreachable("Unknown spill size");
6911  case 16: return X86::VPBROADCASTQZ128rm;
6912  case 32: return X86::VPBROADCASTQZ256rm;
6913  case 64: return X86::VPBROADCASTQZrm;
6914  }
6915  break;
6916  case TB_BCAST_SS:
6917  switch (SpillSize) {
6918  default: llvm_unreachable("Unknown spill size");
6919  case 16: return X86::VBROADCASTSSZ128rm;
6920  case 32: return X86::VBROADCASTSSZ256rm;
6921  case 64: return X86::VBROADCASTSSZrm;
6922  }
6923  break;
6924  case TB_BCAST_SD:
6925  switch (SpillSize) {
6926  default: llvm_unreachable("Unknown spill size");
6927  case 16: return X86::VMOVDDUPZ128rm;
6928  case 32: return X86::VBROADCASTSDZ256rm;
6929  case 64: return X86::VBROADCASTSDZrm;
6930  }
6931  break;
6932  }
6933 }
6934 
6935 bool X86InstrInfo::unfoldMemoryOperand(
6936  MachineFunction &MF, MachineInstr &MI, unsigned Reg, bool UnfoldLoad,
6937  bool UnfoldStore, SmallVectorImpl<MachineInstr *> &NewMIs) const {
6938  const X86MemoryFoldTableEntry *I = lookupUnfoldTable(MI.getOpcode());
6939  if (I == nullptr)
6940  return false;
6941  unsigned Opc = I->DstOp;
6942  unsigned Index = I->Flags & TB_INDEX_MASK;
6943  bool FoldedLoad = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_LOAD;
6944  bool FoldedStore = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_STORE;
6945  bool FoldedBCast = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_BCAST;
6946  if (UnfoldLoad && !FoldedLoad)
6947  return false;
6948  UnfoldLoad &= FoldedLoad;
6949  if (UnfoldStore && !FoldedStore)
6950  return false;
6951  UnfoldStore &= FoldedStore;
6952 
6953  const MCInstrDesc &MCID = get(Opc);
6954 
6955  const TargetRegisterClass *RC = getRegClass(MCID, Index, &RI, MF);
6956  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
6957  // TODO: Check if 32-byte or greater accesses are slow too?
6958  if (!MI.hasOneMemOperand() && RC == &X86::VR128RegClass &&
6959  Subtarget.isUnalignedMem16Slow())
6960  // Without memoperands, loadRegFromAddr and storeRegToStackSlot will
6961  // conservatively assume the address is unaligned. That's bad for
6962  // performance.
6963  return false;
6964  SmallVector<MachineOperand, X86::AddrNumOperands> AddrOps;
6965  SmallVector<MachineOperand,2> BeforeOps;
6966  SmallVector<MachineOperand,2> AfterOps;
6967  SmallVector<MachineOperand,4> ImpOps;
6968  for (unsigned i = 0, e = MI.getNumOperands(); i != e; ++i) {
6969  MachineOperand &Op = MI.getOperand(i);
6970  if (i >= Index && i < Index + X86::AddrNumOperands)
6971  AddrOps.push_back(Op);
6972  else if (Op.isReg() && Op.isImplicit())
6973  ImpOps.push_back(Op);
6974  else if (i < Index)
6975  BeforeOps.push_back(Op);
6976  else if (i > Index)
6977  AfterOps.push_back(Op);
6978  }
6979 
6980  // Emit the load or broadcast instruction.
6981  if (UnfoldLoad) {
6982  auto MMOs = extractLoadMMOs(MI.memoperands(), MF);
6983 
6984  unsigned Opc;
6985  if (FoldedBCast) {
6986  Opc = getBroadcastOpcode(I, RC, Subtarget);
6987  } else {
6988  unsigned Alignment = std::max<uint32_t>(TRI.getSpillSize(*RC), 16);
6989  bool isAligned = !MMOs.empty() && MMOs.front()->getAlign() >= Alignment;
6990  Opc = getLoadRegOpcode(Reg, RC, isAligned, Subtarget);
6991  }
6992 
6993  DebugLoc DL;
6994  MachineInstrBuilder MIB = BuildMI(MF, DL, get(Opc), Reg);
6995  for (unsigned i = 0, e = AddrOps.size(); i != e; ++i)
6996  MIB.add(AddrOps[i]);
6997  MIB.setMemRefs(MMOs);
6998  NewMIs.push_back(MIB);
6999 
7000  if (UnfoldStore) {
7001  // Address operands cannot be marked isKill.
7002  for (unsigned i = 1; i != 1 + X86::AddrNumOperands; ++i) {
7003  MachineOperand &MO = NewMIs[0]->getOperand(i);
7004  if (MO.isReg())
7005  MO.setIsKill(false);
7006  }
7007  }
7008  }
7009 
7010  // Emit the data processing instruction.
7011  MachineInstr *DataMI = MF.CreateMachineInstr(MCID, MI.getDebugLoc(), true);
7012  MachineInstrBuilder MIB(MF, DataMI);
7013 
7014  if (FoldedStore)
7015  MIB.addReg(Reg, RegState::Define);
7016  for (MachineOperand &BeforeOp : BeforeOps)
7017  MIB.add(BeforeOp);
7018  if (FoldedLoad)
7019  MIB.addReg(Reg);
7020  for (MachineOperand &AfterOp : AfterOps)
7021  MIB.add(AfterOp);
7022  for (MachineOperand &ImpOp : ImpOps) {
7023  MIB.addReg(ImpOp.getReg(),
7024  getDefRegState(ImpOp.isDef()) |
7025  RegState::Implicit |
7026  getKillRegState(ImpOp.isKill()) |
7027  getDeadRegState(ImpOp.isDead()) |
7028  getUndefRegState(ImpOp.isUndef()));
7029  }
7030  // Change CMP32ri r, 0 back to TEST32rr r, r, etc.
7031  switch (DataMI->getOpcode()) {
7032  default: break;
7033  case X86::CMP64ri32:
7034  case X86::CMP64ri8:
7035  case X86::CMP32ri:
7036  case X86::CMP32ri8:
7037  case X86::CMP16ri:
7038  case X86::CMP16ri8:
7039  case X86::CMP8ri: {
7040  MachineOperand &MO0 = DataMI->getOperand(0);
7041  MachineOperand &MO1 = DataMI->getOperand(1);
7042  if (MO1.isImm() && MO1.getImm() == 0) {
7043  unsigned NewOpc;
7044  switch (DataMI->getOpcode()) {
7045  default: llvm_unreachable("Unreachable!");
7046  case X86::CMP64ri8:
7047  case X86::CMP64ri32: NewOpc = X86::TEST64rr; break;
7048  case X86::CMP32ri8:
7049  case X86::CMP32ri: NewOpc = X86::TEST32rr; break;
7050  case X86::CMP16ri8:
7051  case X86::CMP16ri: NewOpc = X86::TEST16rr; break;
7052  case X86::CMP8ri: NewOpc = X86::TEST8rr; break;
7053  }
7054  DataMI->setDesc(get(NewOpc));
7055  MO1.ChangeToRegister(MO0.getReg(), false);
7056  }
7057  }
7058  }
7059  NewMIs.push_back(DataMI);
7060 
7061  // Emit the store instruction.
7062  if (UnfoldStore) {
7063  const TargetRegisterClass *DstRC = getRegClass(MCID, 0, &RI, MF);
7064  auto MMOs = extractStoreMMOs(MI.memoperands(), MF);
7065  unsigned Alignment = std::max<uint32_t>(TRI.getSpillSize(*DstRC), 16);
7066  bool isAligned = !MMOs.empty() && MMOs.front()->getAlign() >= Alignment;
7067  unsigned Opc = getStoreRegOpcode(Reg, DstRC, isAligned, Subtarget);
7068  DebugLoc DL;
7069  MachineInstrBuilder MIB = BuildMI(MF, DL, get(Opc));
7070  for (unsigned i = 0, e = AddrOps.size(); i != e; ++i)
7071  MIB.add(AddrOps[i]);
7072  MIB.addReg(Reg, RegState::Kill);
7073  MIB.setMemRefs(MMOs);
7074  NewMIs.push_back(MIB);
7075  }
7076 
7077  return true;
7078 }
7079 
7080 bool
7081 X86InstrInfo::unfoldMemoryOperand(SelectionDAG &DAG, SDNode *N,
7082  SmallVectorImpl<SDNode*> &NewNodes) const {
7083  if (!N->isMachineOpcode())
7084  return false;
7085 
7086  const X86MemoryFoldTableEntry *I = lookupUnfoldTable(N->getMachineOpcode());
7087  if (I == nullptr)
7088  return false;
7089  unsigned Opc = I->DstOp;
7090  unsigned Index = I->Flags & TB_INDEX_MASK;
7091  bool FoldedLoad = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_LOAD;
7092  bool FoldedStore = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_STORE;
7093  bool FoldedBCast = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_BCAST;
7094  const MCInstrDesc &MCID = get(Opc);
7095  MachineFunction &MF = DAG.getMachineFunction();
7096  const TargetRegisterInfo &TRI = *MF.getSubtarget().getRegisterInfo();
7097  const TargetRegisterClass *RC = getRegClass(MCID, Index, &RI, MF);
7098  unsigned NumDefs = MCID.NumDefs;
7099  std::vector<SDValue> AddrOps;
7100  std::vector<SDValue> BeforeOps;
7101  std::vector<SDValue> AfterOps;
7102  SDLoc dl(N);
7103  unsigned NumOps = N->getNumOperands();
7104  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NumOps-1; ++i) {
7105  SDValue Op = N->getOperand(i);
7106  if (i >= Index-NumDefs && i < Index-NumDefs + X86::AddrNumOperands)
7107  AddrOps.push_back(Op);
7108  else if (i < Index-NumDefs)
7109  BeforeOps.push_back(Op);
7110  else if (i > Index-NumDefs)
7111  AfterOps.push_back(Op);
7112  }
7113  SDValue Chain = N->getOperand(NumOps-1);
7114  AddrOps.push_back(Chain);
7115 
7116  // Emit the load instruction.
7117  SDNode *Load = nullptr;
7118  if (FoldedLoad) {
7119  EVT VT = *TRI.legalclasstypes_begin(*RC);
7120  auto MMOs = extractLoadMMOs(cast<MachineSDNode>(N)->memoperands(), MF);
7121  if (MMOs.empty() && RC == &X86::VR128RegClass &&
7122  Subtarget.isUnalignedMem16Slow())
7123  // Do not introduce a slow unaligned load.
7124  return false;
7125  // FIXME: If a VR128 can have size 32, we should be checking if a 32-byte
7126  // memory access is slow above.
7127 
7128  unsigned Opc;
7129  if (FoldedBCast) {
7130  Opc = getBroadcastOpcode(I, RC, Subtarget);
7131  } else {
7132  unsigned Alignment = std::max<uint32_t>(TRI.getSpillSize(*RC), 16);
7133  bool isAligned = !MMOs.empty() && MMOs.front()->getAlign() >= Alignment;
7134  Opc = getLoadRegOpcode(0, RC, isAligned, Subtarget);
7135  }
7136 
7137  Load = DAG.getMachineNode(Opc, dl, VT, MVT::Other, AddrOps);
7138  NewNodes.push_back(Load);
7139 
7140  // Preserve memory reference information.
7141  DAG.setNodeMemRefs(cast<MachineSDNode>(Load), MMOs);
7142  }
7143 
7144  // Emit the data processing instruction.
7145  std::vector<EVT> VTs;
7146  const TargetRegisterClass *DstRC = nullptr;
7147  if (MCID.getNumDefs() > 0) {
7148  DstRC = getRegClass(MCID, 0, &RI, MF);
7149  VTs.push_back(*TRI.legalclasstypes_begin(*DstRC));
7150  }
7151  for (unsigned i = 0, e = N->getNumValues(); i != e; ++i) {
7152  EVT VT = N->getValueType(i);
7153  if (VT != MVT::Other && i >= (unsigned)MCID.getNumDefs())
7154  VTs.push_back(VT);
7155  }
7156  if (Load)
7157  BeforeOps.push_back(SDValue(Load, 0));
7158  llvm::append_range(BeforeOps, AfterOps);
7159  // Change CMP32ri r, 0 back to TEST32rr r, r, etc.
7160  switch (Opc) {
7161  default: break;
7162  case X86::CMP64ri32:
7163  case X86::CMP64ri8:
7164  case X86::CMP32ri:
7165  case X86::CMP32ri8:
7166  case X86::CMP16ri:
7167  case X86::CMP16ri8:
7168  case X86::CMP8ri:
7169  if (isNullConstant(BeforeOps[1])) {
7170  switch (Opc) {
7171  default: llvm_unreachable("Unreachable!");
7172  case X86::CMP64ri8:
7173  case X86::CMP64ri32: Opc = X86::TEST64rr; break;
7174  case X86::CMP32ri8:
7175  case X86::CMP32ri: Opc = X86::TEST32rr; break;
7176  case X86::CMP16ri8:
7177  case X86::CMP16ri: Opc = X86::TEST16rr; break;
7178  case X86::CMP8ri: Opc = X86::TEST8rr; break;
7179  }
7180  BeforeOps[1] = BeforeOps[0];
7181  }
7182  }
7183  SDNode *NewNode= DAG.getMachineNode(Opc, dl, VTs, BeforeOps);
7184  NewNodes.push_back(NewNode);
7185 
7186  // Emit the store instruction.
7187  if (FoldedStore) {
7188  AddrOps.pop_back();
7189  AddrOps.push_back(SDValue(NewNode, 0));
7190  AddrOps.push_back(Chain);
7191  auto MMOs = extractStoreMMOs(cast<MachineSDNode>(N)->memoperands(), MF);
7192  if (MMOs.empty() && RC == &X86::VR128RegClass &&
7193  Subtarget.isUnalignedMem16Slow())
7194  // Do not introduce a slow unaligned store.
7195  return false;
7196  // FIXME: If a VR128 can have size 32, we should be checking if a 32-byte
7197  // memory access is slow above.
7198  unsigned Alignment = std::max<uint32_t>(TRI.getSpillSize(*RC), 16);
7199  bool isAligned = !MMOs.empty() && MMOs.front()->getAlign() >= Alignment;
7200  SDNode *Store =
7201  DAG.getMachineNode(getStoreRegOpcode(0, DstRC, isAligned, Subtarget),
7202  dl, MVT::Other, AddrOps);
7203  NewNodes.push_back(Store);
7204 
7205  // Preserve memory reference information.
7206  DAG.setNodeMemRefs(cast<MachineSDNode>(Store), MMOs);
7207  }
7208 
7209  return true;
7210 }
7211 
7212 unsigned X86InstrInfo::getOpcodeAfterMemoryUnfold(unsigned Opc,
7213  bool UnfoldLoad, bool UnfoldStore,
7214  unsigned *LoadRegIndex) const {
7215  const X86MemoryFoldTableEntry *I = lookupUnfoldTable(Opc);
7216  if (I == nullptr)
7217  return 0;
7218  bool FoldedLoad = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_LOAD;
7219  bool FoldedStore = I->Flags & TB_FOLDED_STORE;
7220  if (UnfoldLoad && !FoldedLoad)
7221  return 0;
7222  if (UnfoldStore && !FoldedStore)
7223  return 0;
7224  if (LoadRegIndex)
7225  *LoadRegIndex = I->Flags & TB_INDEX_MASK;
7226  return I->DstOp;
7227 }
7228 
7229 bool
7230 X86InstrInfo::areLoadsFromSameBasePtr(SDNode *Load1, SDNode *Load2,
7231  int64_t &Offset1, int64_t &Offset2) const {
7232  if (!Load1->isMachineOpcode() || !Load2->isMachineOpcode())
7233  return false;
7234  unsigned Opc1 = Load1->getMachineOpcode();
7235  unsigned Opc2 = Load2->getMachineOpcode();
7236  switch (Opc1) {
7237  default: return false;
7238  case X86::MOV8rm:
7239  case X86::MOV16rm:
7240  case X86::MOV32rm:
7241  case X86::MOV64rm:
7242  case X86::LD_Fp32m:
7243  case X86::LD_Fp64m:
7244  case X86::LD_Fp80m:
7245  case X86::MOVSSrm:
7246  case X86::MOVSSrm_alt:
7247  case X86::MOVSDrm:
7248  case X86::MOVSDrm_alt:
7249  case X86::MMX_MOVD64rm:
7250  case X86::MMX_MOVQ64rm:
7251  case X86::MOVAPSrm:
7252  case X86::MOVUPSrm:
7253  case X86::MOVAPDrm:
7254  case X86::MOVUPDrm:
7255  case X86::MOVDQArm:
7256  case X86::MOVDQUrm:
7257  // AVX load instructions
7258  case X86::VMOVSSrm:
7259  case X86::VMOVSSrm_alt:
7260  case X86::VMOVSDrm:
7261  case X86::VMOVSDrm_alt:
7262  case X86::VMOVAPSrm:
7263  case X86::VMOVUPSrm:
7264  case X86::VMOVAPDrm:
7265  case X86::VMOVUPDrm:
7266  case X86::VMOVDQArm:
7267  case X86::VMOVDQUrm:
7268  case X86::VMOVAPSYrm:
7269  case X86::VMOVUPSYrm:
7270  case X86::VMOVAPDYrm:
7271  case X86::VMOVUPDYrm:
7272  case X86::VMOVDQAYrm:
7273  case X86::VMOVDQUYrm:
7274  // AVX512 load instructions
7275  case X86::VMOVSSZrm:
7276  case X86::VMOVSSZrm_alt:
7277  case X86::VMOVSDZrm:
7278  case X86::VMOVSDZrm_alt:
7279  case X86::VMOVAPSZ128rm:
7280  case X86::VMOVUPSZ128rm:
7281  case X86::VMOVAPSZ128rm_NOVLX:
7282  case X86::VMOVUPSZ128rm_NOVLX:
7283  case X86::VMOVAPDZ128rm:
7284  case X86::VMOVUPDZ128rm:
7285  case X86::VMOVDQU8Z128rm:
7286  case X86::VMOVDQU16Z128rm:
7287  case X86::VMOVDQA32Z128rm:
7288  case X86::VMOVDQU32Z128rm:
7289  case X86::VMOVDQA64Z128rm:
7290  case X86::VMOVDQU64Z128rm:
7291  case X86::VMOVAPSZ256rm:
7292  case X86::VMOVUPSZ256rm:
7293  case X86::VMOVAPSZ256rm_NOVLX:
7294  case X86::VMOVUPSZ256rm_NOVLX:
7295  case X86::VMOVAPDZ256rm:
7296  case X86::VMOVUPDZ256rm:
7297  case X86::VMOVDQU8Z256rm:
7298  case X86::VMOVDQU16Z256rm:
7299  case X86::VMOVDQA32Z256rm:
7300  case X86::VMOVDQU32Z256rm:
7301  case X86::VMOVDQA64Z256rm:
7302  case X86::VMOVDQU64Z256rm:
7303  case X86::VMOVAPSZrm:
7304  case X86::VMOVUPSZrm:
7305  case X86::VMOVAPDZrm:
7306  case X86::VMOVUPDZrm:
7307  case X86::VMOVDQU8Zrm:
7308  case X86::VMOVDQU16Zrm:
7309  case X86::VMOVDQA32Zrm:
7310  case X86::VMOVDQU32Zrm:
7311  case X86::VMOVDQA64Zrm:
7312  case X86::VMOVDQU64Zrm:
7313  case X86::KMOVBkm:
7314  case X86::KMOVWkm:
7315  case X86::KMOVDkm:
7316  case X86::KMOVQkm:
7317  break;
7318  }
7319  switch (Opc2) {
7320  default: return false;
7321  case X86::MOV8rm:
7322  case X86::MOV16rm:
7323  case X86::MOV32rm:
7324  case X86::MOV64rm:
7325  case X86::LD_Fp32m:
7326  case X86::LD_Fp64m:
7327  case X86::LD_Fp80m:
7328  case X86::MOVSSrm:
7329  case X86::MOVSSrm_alt:
7330  case X86::MOVSDrm:
7331  case X86::MOVSDrm_alt:
7332  case X86::MMX_MOVD64rm:
7333  case X86::MMX_MOVQ64rm:
7334  case X86::MOVAPSrm:
7335  case X86::MOVUPSrm:
7336  case X86::MOVAPDrm:
7337  case X86::MOVUPDrm:
7338  case X86::MOVDQArm:
7339  case X86::MOVDQUrm:
7340  // AVX load instructions
7341  case X86::VMOVSSrm:
7342  case X86::VMOVSSrm_alt:
7343  case X86::VMOVSDrm:
7344  case X86::VMOVSDrm_alt:
7345  case X86::VMOVAPSrm:
7346  case X86::VMOVUPSrm:
7347  case X86::VMOVAPDrm:
7348  case X86::VMOVUPDrm:
7349  case X86::VMOVDQArm:
7350  case X86::VMOVDQUrm:
7351  case X86::VMOVAPSYrm:
7352  case X86::VMOVUPSYrm:
7353  case X86::VMOVAPDYrm:
7354  case X86::VMOVUPDYrm:
7355  case X86::VMOVDQAYrm:
7356  case X86::VMOVDQUYrm:
7357  // AVX512 load instructions
7358  case X86::VMOVSSZrm:
7359  case X86::VMOVSSZrm_alt:
7360  case X86::VMOVSDZrm:
7361  case X86::VMOVSDZrm_alt:
7362  case X86::VMOVAPSZ128rm:
7363  case X86::VMOVUPSZ128rm:
7364  case X86::VMOVAPSZ128rm_NOVLX:
7365  case X86::VMOVUPSZ128rm_NOVLX:
7366  case X86::VMOVAPDZ128rm:
7367  case X86::VMOVUPDZ128rm:
7368  case X86::VMOVDQU8Z128rm:
7369  case X86::VMOVDQU16Z128rm:
7370  case X86::VMOVDQA32Z128rm:
7371  case X86::VMOVDQU32Z128rm:
7372  case X86::VMOVDQA64Z128rm:
7373  case X86::VMOVDQU64Z128rm:
7374  case X86::VMOVAPSZ256rm:
7375  case X86::VMOVUPSZ256rm:
7376  case X86::VMOVAPSZ256rm_NOVLX:
7377  case X86::VMOVUPSZ256rm_NOVLX:
7378  case X86::VMOVAPDZ256rm:
7379  case X86::VMOVUPDZ256rm:
7380  case X86::VMOVDQU8Z256rm:
7381  case X86::VMOVDQU16Z256rm:
7382  case X86::VMOVDQA32Z256rm:
7383  case X86::VMOVDQU32Z256rm:
7384  case X86::VMOVDQA64Z256rm:
7385  case X86::VMOVDQU64Z256rm:
7386  case X86::VMOVAPSZrm:
7387  case X86::VMOVUPSZrm:
7388  case X86::VMOVAPDZrm:
7389  case X86::VMOVUPDZrm:
7390  case X86::VMOVDQU8Zrm:
7391  case X86::VMOVDQU16Zrm:
7392  case X86::VMOVDQA32Zrm:
7393  case X86::VMOVDQU32Zrm:
7394  case X86::VMOVDQA64Zrm:
7395  case X86::VMOVDQU64Zrm:
7396  case X86::KMOVBkm:
7397  case X86::KMOVWkm:
7398  case X86::KMOVDkm:
7399  case X86::KMOVQkm:
7400  break;
7401  }
7402 
7403  // Lambda to check if both the loads have the same value for an operand index.
7404  auto HasSameOp = [&](int I) {
7405  return Load1->getOperand(I) == Load2->getOperand(I);
7406  };
7407 
7408  // All operands except the displacement should match.
7409  if (!HasSameOp(X86::AddrBaseReg) || !HasSameOp(X86::AddrScaleAmt) ||
7410  !HasSameOp(X86::AddrIndexReg) || !HasSameOp(X86::AddrSegmentReg))
7411  return false;
7412 
7413  // Chain Operand must be the same.
7414  if (!HasSameOp(5))
7415  return false;
7416 
7417  // Now let's examine if the displacements are constants.
7418  auto Disp1 = dyn_cast<ConstantSDNode>(Load1->getOperand(X86::AddrDisp));
7419  auto Disp2 = dyn_cast<ConstantSDNode>(Load2->getOperand(X86::AddrDisp));
7420  if (!Disp1 || !Disp2)
7421  return false;
7422 
7423  Offset1 = Disp1->getSExtValue();
7424  Offset2 = Disp2->getSExtValue();
7425  return true;
7426 }
7427 
7428 bool X86InstrInfo::shouldScheduleLoadsNear(SDNode *Load1, SDNode *Load2,
7429  int64_t Offset1, int64_t Offset2,
7430  unsigned NumLoads) const {
7431  assert(Offset2 > Offset1);
7432  if ((Offset2 - Offset1) / 8 > 64)
7433  return false;
7434 
7435  unsigned Opc1 = Load1->getMachineOpcode();
7436  unsigned Opc2 = Load2->getMachineOpcode();
7437  if (Opc1 != Opc2)
7438  return false; // FIXME: overly conservative?
7439 
7440  switch (Opc1) {
7441  default: break;
7442  case X86::LD_Fp32m:
7443  case X86::LD_Fp64m:
7444  case X86::LD_Fp80m:
7445  case X86::MMX_MOVD64rm:
7446  case X86::MMX_MOVQ64rm:
7447  return false;
7448  }
7449 
7450  EVT VT = Load1->getValueType(0);
7451  switch (VT.getSimpleVT().SimpleTy) {
7452  default:
7453  // XMM registers. In 64-bit mode we can be a bit more aggressive since we
7454  // have 16 of them to play with.
7455  if (Subtarget.is64Bit()) {
7456  if (NumLoads >= 3)
7457  return false;
7458  } else if (NumLoads) {
7459  return false;
7460  }
7461  break;
7462  case MVT::i8:
7463  case MVT::i16:
7464  case MVT::i32:
7465  case MVT::i64:
7466  case MVT::f32:
7467  case MVT::f64:
7468  if (NumLoads)
7469  return false;
7470  break;
7471  }
7472 
7473  return true;
7474 }
7475 
7476 bool X86InstrInfo::isSchedulingBoundary(const MachineInstr &MI,
7477  const MachineBasicBlock *MBB,
7478  const MachineFunction &MF) const {
7479 
7480  // ENDBR instructions should not be scheduled around.
7481  unsigned Opcode = MI.getOpcode();
7482  if (Opcode == X86::ENDBR64 || Opcode == X86::ENDBR32 ||
7483  Opcode == X86::PLDTILECFGV)
7484  return true;
7485 
7486  return TargetInstrInfo::isSchedulingBoundary(MI, MBB, MF);
7487 }
7488 
7489 bool X86InstrInfo::
7490 reverseBranchCondition(SmallVectorImpl<MachineOperand> &Cond) const {
7491  assert(Cond.size() == 1 && "Invalid X86 branch condition!");
7492  X86::CondCode CC = static_cast<X86::CondCode>(Cond[0].getImm());
7493  Cond[0].setImm(GetOppositeBranchCondition(CC));
7494  return false;
7495 }
7496 
7497 bool X86InstrInfo::
7498 isSafeToMoveRegClassDefs(const TargetRegisterClass *RC) const {
7499  // FIXME: Return false for x87 stack register classes for now. We can't
7500  // allow any loads of these registers before FpGet_ST0_80.
7501  return !(RC == &X86::CCRRegClass || RC == &X86::DFCCRRegClass ||
7502  RC == &X86::RFP32RegClass || RC == &X86::RFP64RegClass ||
7503  RC == &X86::RFP80RegClass);
7504 }
7505 
7506 /// Return a virtual register initialized with the
7507 /// the global base register value. Output instructions required to
7508 /// initialize the register in the function entry block, if necessary.
7509 ///
7510 /// TODO: Eliminate this and move the code to X86MachineFunctionInfo.
7511 ///
7512 unsigned X86InstrInfo::getGlobalBaseReg(MachineFunction *MF) const {
7513  assert((!Subtarget.is64Bit() ||
7514  MF->getTarget().getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Medium ||
7515  MF->getTarget().getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Large) &&
7516  "X86-64 PIC uses RIP relative addressing");
7517 
7518  X86MachineFunctionInfo *X86FI = MF->getInfo<X86MachineFunctionInfo>();
7519  Register GlobalBaseReg = X86FI->getGlobalBaseReg();
7520  if (GlobalBaseReg != 0)
7521  return GlobalBaseReg;
7522 
7523  // Create the register. The code to initialize it is inserted
7524  // later, by the CGBR pass (below).
7525  MachineRegisterInfo &RegInfo = MF->getRegInfo();
7526  GlobalBaseReg = RegInfo.createVirtualRegister(
7527  Subtarget.is64Bit() ? &X86::GR64_NOSPRegClass : &X86::GR32_NOSPRegClass);
7528  X86FI->setGlobalBaseReg(GlobalBaseReg);
7529  return GlobalBaseReg;
7530 }

7993 // NOTE: These should only be used by the custom domain methods.

8033 
8034 // FIXME: Some shuffle and unpack instructions have equivalents in different
8035 // domains, but they require a bit more work than just switching opcodes.
8036 
8037 static const uint16_t *lookup(unsigned opcode, unsigned domain,
8038  ArrayRef<uint16_t[3]> Table) {
8039  for (const uint16_t (&Row)[3] : Table)
8040  if (Row[domain-1] == opcode)
8041  return Row;
8042  return nullptr;
8043 }
8044 
8045 static const uint16_t *lookupAVX512(unsigned opcode, unsigned domain,
8046  ArrayRef<uint16_t[4]> Table) {
8047  // If this is the integer domain make sure to check both integer columns.
8048  for (const uint16_t (&Row)[4] : Table)
8049  if (Row[domain-1] == opcode || (domain == 3 && Row[3] == opcode))
8050  return Row;
8051  return nullptr;
8052 }
8053 
8054 // Helper to attempt to widen/narrow blend masks.
8055 static bool AdjustBlendMask(unsigned OldMask, unsigned OldWidth,
8056  unsigned NewWidth, unsigned *pNewMask = nullptr) {
8057  assert(((OldWidth % NewWidth) == 0 || (NewWidth % OldWidth) == 0) &&
8058  "Illegal blend mask scale");
8059  unsigned NewMask = 0;
8060 
8061  if ((OldWidth % NewWidth) == 0) {
8062  unsigned Scale = OldWidth / NewWidth;
8063  unsigned SubMask = (1u << Scale) - 1;
8064  for (unsigned i = 0; i != NewWidth; ++i) {
8065  unsigned Sub = (OldMask >> (i * Scale)) & SubMask;
8066  if (Sub == SubMask)
8067  NewMask |= (1u << i);
8068  else if (Sub != 0x0)
8069  return false;
8070  }
8071  } else {
8072  unsigned Scale = NewWidth / OldWidth;
8073  unsigned SubMask = (1u << Scale) - 1;
8074  for (unsigned i = 0; i != OldWidth; ++i) {
8075  if (OldMask & (1 << i)) {
8076  NewMask |= (SubMask << (i * Scale));
8077  }
8078  }
8079  }
8080 
8081  if (pNewMask)
8082  *pNewMask = NewMask;
8083  return true;
8084 }
8085 
8086 uint16_t X86InstrInfo::getExecutionDomainCustom(const MachineInstr &MI) const {
8087  unsigned Opcode = MI.getOpcode();
8088  unsigned NumOperands = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands();
8089 
8090  auto GetBlendDomains = [&](unsigned ImmWidth, bool Is256) {
8091  uint16_t validDomains = 0;
8092  if (MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1).isImm()) {
8093  unsigned Imm = MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1).getImm();
8094  if (AdjustBlendMask(Imm, ImmWidth, Is256 ? 8 : 4))
8095  validDomains |= 0x2; // PackedSingle
8096  if (AdjustBlendMask(Imm, ImmWidth, Is256 ? 4 : 2))
8097  validDomains |= 0x4; // PackedDouble
8098  if (!Is256 || Subtarget.hasAVX2())
8099  validDomains |= 0x8; // PackedInt
8100  }
8101  return validDomains;
8102  };
8103 
8104  switch (Opcode) {
8105  case X86::BLENDPDrmi:
8106  case X86::BLENDPDrri:
8107  case X86::VBLENDPDrmi:
8108  case X86::VBLENDPDrri:
8109  return GetBlendDomains(2, false);
8110  case X86::VBLENDPDYrmi:
8111  case X86::VBLENDPDYrri:
8112  return GetBlendDomains(4, true);
8113  case X86::BLENDPSrmi:
8114  case X86::BLENDPSrri:
8115  case X86::VBLENDPSrmi:
8116  case X86::VBLENDPSrri:
8117  case X86::VPBLENDDrmi:
8118  case X86::VPBLENDDrri:
8119  return GetBlendDomains(4, false);
8120  case X86::VBLENDPSYrmi:
8121  case X86::VBLENDPSYrri:
8122  case X86::VPBLENDDYrmi:
8123  case X86::VPBLENDDYrri:
8124  return GetBlendDomains(8, true);
8125  case X86::PBLENDWrmi:
8126  case X86::PBLENDWrri:
8127  case X86::VPBLENDWrmi:
8128  case X86::VPBLENDWrri:
8129  // Treat VPBLENDWY as a 128-bit vector as it repeats the lo/hi masks.
8130  case X86::VPBLENDWYrmi:
8131  case X86::VPBLENDWYrri:
8132  return GetBlendDomains(8, false);
8133  case X86::VPANDDZ128rr: case X86::VPANDDZ128rm:
8134  case X86::VPANDDZ256rr: case X86::VPANDDZ256rm:
8135  case X86::VPANDQZ128rr: case X86::VPANDQZ128rm:
8136  case X86::VPANDQZ256rr: case X86::VPANDQZ256rm:
8137  case X86::VPANDNDZ128rr: case X86::VPANDNDZ128rm:
8138  case X86::VPANDNDZ256rr: case X86::VPANDNDZ256rm:
8139  case X86::VPANDNQZ128rr: case X86::VPANDNQZ128rm:
8140  case X86::VPANDNQZ256rr: case X86::VPANDNQZ256rm:
8141  case X86::VPORDZ128rr: case X86::VPORDZ128rm:
8142  case X86::VPORDZ256rr: case X86::VPORDZ256rm:
8143  case X86::VPORQZ128rr: case X86::VPORQZ128rm:
8144  case X86::VPORQZ256rr: case X86::VPORQZ256rm:
8145  case X86::VPXORDZ128rr: case X86::VPXORDZ128rm:
8146  case X86::VPXORDZ256rr: case X86::VPXORDZ256rm:
8147  case X86::VPXORQZ128rr: case X86::VPXORQZ128rm:
8148  case X86::VPXORQZ256rr: case X86::VPXORQZ256rm:
8149  // If we don't have DQI see if we can still switch from an EVEX integer
8150  // instruction to a VEX floating point instruction.
8151  if (Subtarget.hasDQI())
8152  return 0;
8153 
8154  if (RI.getEncodingValue(MI.getOperand(0).getReg()) >= 16)
8155  return 0;
8156  if (RI.getEncodingValue(MI.getOperand(1).getReg()) >= 16)
8157  return 0;
8158  // Register forms will have 3 operands. Memory form will have more.
8159  if (NumOperands == 3 &&
8160  RI.getEncodingValue(MI.getOperand(2).getReg()) >= 16)
8161  return 0;
8162 
8163  // All domains are valid.
8164  return 0xe;
8165  case X86::MOVHLPSrr:
8166  // We can swap domains when both inputs are the same register.
8167  // FIXME: This doesn't catch all the cases we would like. If the input
8168  // register isn't KILLed by the instruction, the two address instruction
8169  // pass puts a COPY on one input. The other input uses the original
8170  // register. This prevents the same physical register from being used by
8171  // both inputs.
8172  if (MI.getOperand(1).getReg() == MI.getOperand(2).getReg() &&
8173  MI.getOperand(0).getSubReg() == 0 &&
8174  MI.getOperand(1).getSubReg() == 0 &&
8175  MI.getOperand(2).getSubReg() == 0)
8176  return 0x6;
8177  return 0;
8178  case X86::SHUFPDrri:
8179  return 0x6;
8180  }
8181  return 0;
8182 }
8183 
8184 bool X86InstrInfo::setExecutionDomainCustom(MachineInstr &MI,
8185  unsigned Domain) const {
8186  assert(Domain > 0 && Domain < 4 && "Invalid execution domain");
8187  uint16_t dom = (MI.getDesc().TSFlags >> X86II::SSEDomainShift) & 3;
8188  assert(dom && "Not an SSE instruction");
8189 
8190  unsigned Opcode = MI.getOpcode();
8191  unsigned NumOperands = MI.getDesc().getNumOperands();
8192 
8193  auto SetBlendDomain = [&](unsigned ImmWidth, bool Is256) {
8194  if (MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1).isImm()) {
8195  unsigned Imm = MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1).getImm() & 255;
8196  Imm = (ImmWidth == 16 ? ((Imm << 8) | Imm) : Imm);
8197  unsigned NewImm = Imm;
8198 
8199  const uint16_t *table = lookup(Opcode, dom, ReplaceableBlendInstrs);
8200  if (!table)
8201  table = lookup(Opcode, dom, ReplaceableBlendAVX2Instrs);
8202 
8203  if (Domain == 1) { // PackedSingle
8204  AdjustBlendMask(Imm, ImmWidth, Is256 ? 8 : 4, &NewImm);
8205  } else if (Domain == 2) { // PackedDouble
8206  AdjustBlendMask(Imm, ImmWidth, Is256 ? 4 : 2, &NewImm);
8207  } else if (Domain == 3) { // PackedInt
8208  if (Subtarget.hasAVX2()) {
8209  // If we are already VPBLENDW use that, else use VPBLENDD.
8210  if ((ImmWidth / (Is256 ? 2 : 1)) != 8) {
8211  table = lookup(Opcode, dom, ReplaceableBlendAVX2Instrs);
8212  AdjustBlendMask(Imm, ImmWidth, Is256 ? 8 : 4, &NewImm);
8213  }
8214  } else {
8215  assert(!Is256 && "128-bit vector expected");
8216  AdjustBlendMask(Imm, ImmWidth, 8, &NewImm);
8217  }
8218  }
8219 
8220  assert(table && table[Domain - 1] && "Unknown domain op");
8221  MI.setDesc(get(table[Domain - 1]));
8222  MI.getOperand(NumOperands - 1).setImm(NewImm & 255);
8223  }
8224  return true;
8225  };
8226 
8227  switch (Opcode) {
8228  case X86::BLENDPDrmi:
8229  case X86::BLENDPDrri:
8230  case X86::VBLENDPDrmi:
8231  case X86::VBLENDPDrri:
8232  return SetBlendDomain(2, false);
8233  case X86::VBLENDPDYrmi:
8234  case X86::VBLENDPDYrri:
8235  return SetBlendDomain(4, true);
8236  case X86::BLENDPSrmi:
8237  case X86::BLENDPSrri:
8238  case X86::VBLENDPSrmi:
8239  case X86::VBLENDPSrri:
8240  case X86::VPBLENDDrmi:
8241  case X86::VPBLENDDrri:
8242  return SetBlendDomain(4, false);
8243  case X86::VBLENDPSYrmi:
8244  case X86::VBLENDPSYrri:
8245  case X86::VPBLENDDYrmi:
8246  case X86::VPBLENDDYrri:
8247  return SetBlendDomain(8, true);
8248  case X86::PBLENDWrmi:
8249  case X86::PBLENDWrri:
8250  case X86::VPBLENDWrmi:
8251  case X86::VPBLENDWrri:
8252  return SetBlendDomain(8, false);
8253  case X86::VPBLENDWYrmi:
8254  case X86::VPBLENDWYrri:
8255  return SetBlendDomain(16, true);
8256  case X86::VPANDDZ128rr: case X86::VPANDDZ128rm:
8257  case X86::VPANDDZ256rr: case X86::VPANDDZ256rm:
8258  case X86::VPANDQZ128rr: case X86::VPANDQZ128rm:
8259  case X86::VPANDQZ256rr: case X86::VPANDQZ256rm:
8260  case X86::VPANDNDZ128rr: case X86::VPANDNDZ128rm:
8261  case X86::VPANDNDZ256rr: case X86::VPANDNDZ256rm:
8262  case X86::VPANDNQZ128rr: case X86::VPANDNQZ128rm:
8263  case X86::VPANDNQZ256rr: case X86::VPANDNQZ256rm:
8264  case X86::VPORDZ128rr: case X86::VPORDZ128rm:
8265  case X86::VPORDZ256rr: case X86::VPORDZ256rm:
8266  case X86::VPORQZ128rr: case X86::VPORQZ128rm:
8267  case X86::VPORQZ256rr: case X86::VPORQZ256rm:
8268  case X86::VPXORDZ128rr: case X86::VPXORDZ128rm:
8269  case X86::VPXORDZ256rr: case X86::VPXORDZ256rm:
8270  case X86::VPXORQZ128rr: case X86::VPXORQZ128rm:
8271  case X86::VPXORQZ256rr: case X86::VPXORQZ256rm: {
8272  // Without DQI, convert EVEX instructions to VEX instructions.
8273  if (Subtarget.hasDQI())
8274  return false;
8275 
8276  const uint16_t *table = lookupAVX512(MI.getOpcode(), dom,
8277  ReplaceableCustomAVX512LogicInstrs);
8278  assert(table && "Instruction not found in table?");
8279  // Don't change integer Q instructions to D instructions and
8280  // use D intructions if we started with a PS instruction.
8281  if (Domain == 3 && (dom == 1 || table[3] == MI.getOpcode()))
8282  Domain = 4;
8283  MI.setDesc(get(table[Domain - 1]));
8284  return true;
8285  }
8286  case X86::UNPCKHPDrr:
8287  case X86::MOVHLPSrr:
8288  // We just need to commute the instruction which will switch the domains.
8289  if (Domain != dom && Domain != 3 &&
8290  MI.getOperand(1).getReg() == MI.getOperand(2).getReg() &&
8291  MI.getOperand(0).getSubReg() == 0 &&
8292  MI.getOperand(1).getSubReg() == 0 &&
8293  MI.getOperand(2).getSubReg() == 0) {
8294  commuteInstruction(MI, false);
8295  return true;
8296  }
8297  // We must always return true for MOVHLPSrr.
8298  if (Opcode == X86::MOVHLPSrr)
8299  return true;
8300  break;
8301  case X86::SHUFPDrri: {
8302  if (Domain == 1) {
8303  unsigned Imm = MI.getOperand(3).getImm();
8304  unsigned NewImm = 0x44;
8305  if (Imm & 1) NewImm |= 0x0a;
8306  if (Imm & 2) NewImm |= 0xa0;
8307  MI.getOperand(3).setImm(NewImm);
8308  MI.setDesc(get(X86::SHUFPSrri));
8309  }
8310  return true;
8311  }
8312  }
8313  return false;
8314 }
8315 
8316 std::pair<uint16_t, uint16_t>
8317 X86InstrInfo::getExecutionDomain(const MachineInstr &MI) const {
8318  uint16_t domain = (MI.getDesc().TSFlags >> X86II::SSEDomainShift) & 3;
8319  unsigned opcode = MI.getOpcode();
8320  uint16_t validDomains = 0;
8321  if (domain) {
8322  // Attempt to match for custom instructions.
8323  validDomains = getExecutionDomainCustom(MI);
8324  if (validDomains)
8325  return std::make_pair(domain, validDomains);
8326 
8327  if (lookup(opcode, domain, ReplaceableInstrs)) {
8328  validDomains = 0xe;
8329  } else if (lookup(opcode, domain, ReplaceableInstrsAVX2)) {
8330  validDomains = Subtarget.hasAVX2() ? 0xe : 0x6;
8331  } else if (lookup(opcode, domain, ReplaceableInstrsFP)) {
8332  validDomains = 0x6;
8333  } else if (lookup(opcode, domain, ReplaceableInstrsAVX2InsertExtract)) {
8334  // Insert/extract instructions should only effect domain if AVX2
8335  // is enabled.
8336  if (!Subtarget.hasAVX2())
8337  return std::make_pair(0, 0);
8338  validDomains = 0xe;
8339  } else if (lookupAVX512(opcode, domain, ReplaceableInstrsAVX512)) {
8340  validDomains = 0xe;
8341  } else if (Subtarget.hasDQI() && lookupAVX512(opcode, domain,
8342  ReplaceableInstrsAVX512DQ)) {
8343  validDomains = 0xe;
8344  } else if (Subtarget.hasDQI()) {
8345  if (const uint16_t *table = lookupAVX512(opcode, domain,
8346  ReplaceableInstrsAVX512DQMasked)) {
8347  if (domain == 1 || (domain == 3 && table[3] == opcode))
8348  validDomains = 0xa;
8349  else
8350  validDomains = 0xc;
8351  }
8352  }
8353  }
8354  return std::make_pair(domain, validDomains);
8355 }
8356 
8357 void X86InstrInfo::setExecutionDomain(MachineInstr &MI, unsigned Domain) const {
8358  assert(Domain>0 && Domain<4 && "Invalid execution domain");
8359  uint16_t dom = (MI.getDesc().TSFlags >> X86II::SSEDomainShift) & 3;
8360  assert(dom && "Not an SSE instruction");
8361 
8362  // Attempt to match for custom instructions.
8363  if (setExecutionDomainCustom(MI, Domain))
8364  return;
8365 
8366  const uint16_t *table = lookup(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrs);
8367  if (!table) { // try the other table
8368  assert((Subtarget.hasAVX2() || Domain < 3) &&
8369  "256-bit vector operations only available in AVX2");
8370  table = lookup(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrsAVX2);
8371  }
8372  if (!table) { // try the FP table
8373  table = lookup(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrsFP);
8374  assert((!table || Domain < 3) &&
8375  "Can only select PackedSingle or PackedDouble");
8376  }
8377  if (!table) { // try the other table
8378  assert(Subtarget.hasAVX2() &&
8379  "256-bit insert/extract only available in AVX2");
8380  table = lookup(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrsAVX2InsertExtract);
8381  }
8382  if (!table) { // try the AVX512 table
8383  assert(Subtarget.hasAVX512() && "Requires AVX-512");
8384  table = lookupAVX512(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrsAVX512);
8385  // Don't change integer Q instructions to D instructions.
8386  if (table && Domain == 3 && table[3] == MI.getOpcode())
8387  Domain = 4;
8388  }
8389  if (!table) { // try the AVX512DQ table
8390  assert((Subtarget.hasDQI() || Domain >= 3) && "Requires AVX-512DQ");
8391  table = lookupAVX512(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrsAVX512DQ);
8392  // Don't change integer Q instructions to D instructions and
8393  // use D instructions if we started with a PS instruction.
8394  if (table && Domain == 3 && (dom == 1 || table[3] == MI.getOpcode()))
8395  Domain = 4;
8396  }
8397  if (!table) { // try the AVX512DQMasked table
8398  assert((Subtarget.hasDQI() || Domain >= 3) && "Requires AVX-512DQ");
8399  table = lookupAVX512(MI.getOpcode(), dom, ReplaceableInstrsAVX512DQMasked);
8400  if (table && Domain == 3 && (dom == 1 || table[3] == MI.getOpcode()))
8401  Domain = 4;
8402  }
8403  assert(table && "Cannot change domain");
8404  MI.setDesc(get(table[Domain - 1]));
8405 }
8406 
8407 /// Return the noop instruction to use for a noop.
8408 MCInst X86InstrInfo::getNop() const {
8409  MCInst Nop;
8410  Nop.setOpcode(X86::NOOP);
8411  return Nop;
8412 }

8724 bool X86InstrInfo::hasHighOperandLatency(const TargetSchedModel &SchedModel,

8732 
8733 bool X86InstrInfo::hasReassociableOperands(const MachineInstr &Inst,
8734  const MachineBasicBlock *MBB) const {
8735  assert(Inst.getNumExplicitOperands() == 3 && Inst.getNumExplicitDefs() == 1 &&
8736  Inst.getNumDefs() <= 2 && "Reassociation needs binary operators");
8737 
8738  // Integer binary math/logic instructions have a third source operand:
8739  // the EFLAGS register. That operand must be both defined here and never
8740  // used; ie, it must be dead. If the EFLAGS operand is live, then we can
8741  // not change anything because rearranging the operands could affect other
8742  // instructions that depend on the exact status flags (zero, sign, etc.)
8743  // that are set by using these particular operands with this operation.
8744  const MachineOperand *FlagDef = Inst.findRegisterDefOperand(X86::EFLAGS);
8745  assert((Inst.getNumDefs() == 1 || FlagDef) &&
8746  "Implicit def isn't flags?");
8747  if (FlagDef && !FlagDef->isDead())
8748  return false;
8749 
8750  return TargetInstrInfo::hasReassociableOperands(Inst, MBB);
8751 }
8752 
8753 // TODO: There are many more machine instruction opcodes to match:
8754 // 1. Other data types (integer, vectors)
8755 // 2. Other math / logic operations (xor, or)
8756 // 3. Other forms of the same operation (intrinsics and other variants)
8757 bool X86InstrInfo::isAssociativeAndCommutative(const MachineInstr &Inst,
8758  bool Invert) const {
