9081 
9082 /// If \p DescribedReg overlaps with the MOVrr instruction's destination
9083 /// register then, if possible, describe the value in terms of the source
9084 /// register.
9085 static std::optional<ParamLoadedValue>
9086 describeMOVrrLoadedValue(const MachineInstr &MI, Register DescribedReg,
9087  const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI) {
9088  Register DestReg = MI.getOperand(0).getReg();
9089  Register SrcReg = MI.getOperand(1).getReg();
9090 
9091  auto Expr = DIExpression::get(MI.getMF()->getFunction().getContext(), {});
9092 
9093  // If the described register is the destination, just return the source.
9094  if (DestReg == DescribedReg)
9095  return ParamLoadedValue(MachineOperand::CreateReg(SrcReg, false), Expr);
9096 
9097  // If the described register is a sub-register of the destination register,
9098  // then pick out the source register's corresponding sub-register.
9099  if (unsigned SubRegIdx = TRI->getSubRegIndex(DestReg, DescribedReg)) {
9100  Register SrcSubReg = TRI->getSubReg(SrcReg, SubRegIdx);
9101  return ParamLoadedValue(MachineOperand::CreateReg(SrcSubReg, false), Expr);
9102  }
9103 
9104  // The remaining case to consider is when the described register is a
9105  // super-register of the destination register. MOV8rr and MOV16rr does not
9106  // write to any of the other bytes in the register, meaning that we'd have to
9107  // describe the value using a combination of the source register and the
9108  // non-overlapping bits in the described register, which is not currently
9109  // possible.
9110  if (MI.getOpcode() == X86::MOV8rr || MI.getOpcode() == X86::MOV16rr ||
9111  !TRI->isSuperRegister(DestReg, DescribedReg))
9112  return std::nullopt;
9113 
9114  assert(MI.getOpcode() == X86::MOV32rr && "Unexpected super-register case");
9115  return ParamLoadedValue(MachineOperand::CreateReg(SrcReg, false), Expr);
9116 }
9117 
9118 std::optional<ParamLoadedValue>
9119 X86InstrInfo::describeLoadedValue(const MachineInstr &MI, Register Reg) const {
9120  const MachineOperand *Op = nullptr;
9121  DIExpression *Expr = nullptr;
9122 
9123  const TargetRegisterInfo *TRI = &getRegisterInfo();
9124 
9125  switch (MI.getOpcode()) {
9126  case X86::LEA32r:
9127  case X86::LEA64r:
9128  case X86::LEA64_32r: {
9129  // We may need to describe a 64-bit parameter with a 32-bit LEA.
9130  if (!TRI->isSuperRegisterEq(MI.getOperand(0).getReg(), Reg))
9131  return std::nullopt;
9132 
9133  // Operand 4 could be global address. For now we do not support
9134  // such situation.
9135  if (!MI.getOperand(4).isImm() || !MI.getOperand(2).isImm())
9136  return std::nullopt;
9137 
9138  const MachineOperand &Op1 = MI.getOperand(1);
9139  const MachineOperand &Op2 = MI.getOperand(3);
9140  assert(Op2.isReg() &&
9141  (Op2.getReg() == X86::NoRegister || Op2.getReg().isPhysical()));
9142 
9143  // Omit situations like:
9144  // %rsi = lea %rsi, 4, ...
9145  if ((Op1.isReg() && Op1.getReg() == MI.getOperand(0).getReg()) ||
9146  Op2.getReg() == MI.getOperand(0).getReg())
9147  return std::nullopt;
9148  else if ((Op1.isReg() && Op1.getReg() != X86::NoRegister &&
9149  TRI->regsOverlap(Op1.getReg(), MI.getOperand(0).getReg())) ||
9150  (Op2.getReg() != X86::NoRegister &&
9151  TRI->regsOverlap(Op2.getReg(), MI.getOperand(0).getReg())))
9152  return std::nullopt;
9153 
9154  int64_t Coef = MI.getOperand(2).getImm();
9155  int64_t Offset = MI.getOperand(4).getImm();
9156  SmallVector<uint64_t, 8> Ops;
9157 
9158  if ((Op1.isReg() && Op1.getReg() != X86::NoRegister)) {
9159  Op = &Op1;
9160  } else if (Op1.isFI())
9161  Op = &Op1;
9162 
9163  if (Op && Op->isReg() && Op->getReg() == Op2.getReg() && Coef > 0) {
9164  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_constu);
9165  Ops.push_back(Coef + 1);
9166  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_mul);
9167  } else {
9168  if (Op && Op2.getReg() != X86::NoRegister) {
9169  int dwarfReg = TRI->getDwarfRegNum(Op2.getReg(), false);
9170  if (dwarfReg < 0)
9171  return std::nullopt;
9172  else if (dwarfReg < 32) {
9173  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_breg0 + dwarfReg);
9174  Ops.push_back(0);
9175  } else {
9176  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_bregx);
9177  Ops.push_back(dwarfReg);
9178  Ops.push_back(0);
9179  }
9180  } else if (!Op) {
9181  assert(Op2.getReg() != X86::NoRegister);
9182  Op = &Op2;
9183  }
9184 
9185  if (Coef > 1) {
9186  assert(Op2.getReg() != X86::NoRegister);
9187  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_constu);
9188  Ops.push_back(Coef);
9189  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_mul);
9190  }
9191 
9192  if (((Op1.isReg() && Op1.getReg() != X86::NoRegister) || Op1.isFI()) &&
9193  Op2.getReg() != X86::NoRegister) {
9194  Ops.push_back(dwarf::DW_OP_plus);
9195  }
9196  }
9197 
9198  DIExpression::appendOffset(Ops, Offset);
9199  Expr = DIExpression::get(MI.getMF()->getFunction().getContext(), Ops);
9200 
9201  return ParamLoadedValue(*Op, Expr);;
9202  }
9203  case X86::MOV8ri:
9204  case X86::MOV16ri:
9205  // TODO: Handle MOV8ri and MOV16ri.
9206  return std::nullopt;
9207  case X86::MOV32ri:
9208  case X86::MOV64ri:
9209  case X86::MOV64ri32:
9210  // MOV32ri may be used for producing zero-extended 32-bit immediates in
9211  // 64-bit parameters, so we need to consider super-registers.
9212  if (!TRI->isSuperRegisterEq(MI.getOperand(0).getReg(), Reg))
9213  return std::nullopt;
9214  return ParamLoadedValue(MI.getOperand(1), Expr);
9215  case X86::MOV8rr:
9216  case X86::MOV16rr:
9217  case X86::MOV32rr:
9218  case X86::MOV64rr:
9219  return describeMOVrrLoadedValue(MI, Reg, TRI);
9220  case X86::XOR32rr: {
9221  // 64-bit parameters are zero-materialized using XOR32rr, so also consider
9222  // super-registers.
9223  if (!TRI->isSuperRegisterEq(MI.getOperand(0).getReg(), Reg))
9224  return std::nullopt;
9225  if (MI.getOperand(1).getReg() == MI.getOperand(2).getReg())
9226  return ParamLoadedValue(MachineOperand::CreateImm(0), Expr);
9227  return std::nullopt;
9228  }
9229  case X86::MOVSX64rr32: {
9230  // We may need to describe the lower 32 bits of the MOVSX; for example, in
9231  // cases like this:
9232  //
9233  // $ebx = [...]
9234  // $rdi = MOVSX64rr32 $ebx
9235  // $esi = MOV32rr $edi
9236  if (!TRI->isSubRegisterEq(MI.getOperand(0).getReg(), Reg))
9237  return std::nullopt;
9238 
9239  Expr = DIExpression::get(MI.getMF()->getFunction().getContext(), {});
9240 
9241  // If the described register is the destination register we need to
9242  // sign-extend the source register from 32 bits. The other case we handle
9243  // is when the described register is the 32-bit sub-register of the
9244  // destination register, in case we just need to return the source
9245  // register.
9246  if (Reg == MI.getOperand(0).getReg())
9247  Expr = DIExpression::appendExt(Expr, 32, 64, true);
9248  else
9249  assert(X86MCRegisterClasses[X86::GR32RegClassID].contains(Reg) &&
9250  "Unhandled sub-register case for MOVSX64rr32");
9251 
9252  return ParamLoadedValue(MI.getOperand(1), Expr);
9253  }
9254  default:
9255  assert(!MI.isMoveImmediate() && "Unexpected MoveImm instruction");
9256  return TargetInstrInfo::describeLoadedValue(MI, Reg);
9257  }
9258 }
9259 
9260 /// This is an architecture-specific helper function of reassociateOps.
9261 /// Set special operand attributes for new instructions after reassociation.
9262 void X86InstrInfo::setSpecialOperandAttr(MachineInstr &OldMI1,
9263  MachineInstr &OldMI2,
9264  MachineInstr &NewMI1,
9265  MachineInstr &NewMI2) const {
9266  // Propagate FP flags from the original instructions.
9267  // But clear poison-generating flags because those may not be valid now.
9268  // TODO: There should be a helper function for copying only fast-math-flags.
9269  uint16_t IntersectedFlags = OldMI1.getFlags() & OldMI2.getFlags();
9270  NewMI1.setFlags(IntersectedFlags);
9271  NewMI1.clearFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoSWrap);
9272  NewMI1.clearFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoUWrap);
9273  NewMI1.clearFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::IsExact);
9274 
9275  NewMI2.setFlags(IntersectedFlags);
9276  NewMI2.clearFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoSWrap);
9277  NewMI2.clearFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::NoUWrap);
9278  NewMI2.clearFlag(MachineInstr::MIFlag::IsExact);
9279 
9280  // Integer instructions may define an implicit EFLAGS dest register operand.
9281  MachineOperand *OldFlagDef1 = OldMI1.findRegisterDefOperand(X86::EFLAGS);
9282  MachineOperand *OldFlagDef2 = OldMI2.findRegisterDefOperand(X86::EFLAGS);
9283 
9284  assert(!OldFlagDef1 == !OldFlagDef2 &&
9285  "Unexpected instruction type for reassociation");
9286 
9287  if (!OldFlagDef1 || !OldFlagDef2)
9288  return;
9289 
9290  assert(OldFlagDef1->isDead() && OldFlagDef2->isDead() &&
9291  "Must have dead EFLAGS operand in reassociable instruction");
9292 
9293  MachineOperand *NewFlagDef1 = NewMI1.findRegisterDefOperand(X86::EFLAGS);
9294  MachineOperand *NewFlagDef2 = NewMI2.findRegisterDefOperand(X86::EFLAGS);
9295 
9296  assert(NewFlagDef1 && NewFlagDef2 &&
9297  "Unexpected operand in reassociable instruction");
9298 
9299  // Mark the new EFLAGS operands as dead to be helpful to subsequent iterations
9300  // of this pass or other passes. The EFLAGS operands must be dead in these new
9301  // instructions because the EFLAGS operands in the original instructions must
9302  // be dead in order for reassociation to occur.
9303  NewFlagDef1->setIsDead();
9304  NewFlagDef2->setIsDead();
9305 }
9306 
9307 std::pair<unsigned, unsigned>
9308 X86InstrInfo::decomposeMachineOperandsTargetFlags(unsigned TF) const {
9309  return std::make_pair(TF, 0u);
9310 }

9312 ArrayRef<std::pair<unsigned, const char *>>
9313 X86InstrInfo::getSerializableDirectMachineOperandTargetFlags() const {
9314  using namespace X86II;
9315  static const std::pair<unsigned, const char *> TargetFlags[] = {
9316  {MO_GOT_ABSOLUTE_ADDRESS, "x86-got-absolute-address"},
9317  {MO_PIC_BASE_OFFSET, "x86-pic-base-offset"},
9318  {MO_GOT, "x86-got"},
9319  {MO_GOTOFF, "x86-gotoff"},
9320  {MO_GOTPCREL, "x86-gotpcrel"},
9321  {MO_GOTPCREL_NORELAX, "x86-gotpcrel-norelax"},
9322  {MO_PLT, "x86-plt"},
9323  {MO_TLSGD, "x86-tlsgd"},
9324  {MO_TLSLD, "x86-tlsld"},
9325  {MO_TLSLDM, "x86-tlsldm"},
9326  {MO_GOTTPOFF, "x86-gottpoff"},
9327  {MO_INDNTPOFF, "x86-indntpoff"},
9328  {MO_TPOFF, "x86-tpoff"},
9329  {MO_DTPOFF, "x86-dtpoff"},
9330  {MO_NTPOFF, "x86-ntpoff"},
9331  {MO_GOTNTPOFF, "x86-gotntpoff"},
9332  {MO_DLLIMPORT, "x86-dllimport"},
9333  {MO_DARWIN_NONLAZY, "x86-darwin-nonlazy"},
9334  {MO_DARWIN_NONLAZY_PIC_BASE, "x86-darwin-nonlazy-pic-base"},
9335  {MO_TLVP, "x86-tlvp"},
9336  {MO_TLVP_PIC_BASE, "x86-tlvp-pic-base"},
9337  {MO_SECREL, "x86-secrel"},
9338  {MO_COFFSTUB, "x86-coffstub"}};
9339  return ArrayRef(TargetFlags);
9340 }
9341 
9342 namespace {
9343  /// Create Global Base Reg pass. This initializes the PIC
9344  /// global base register for x86-32.
9345  struct CGBR : public MachineFunctionPass {
9346  static char ID;
9347  CGBR() : MachineFunctionPass(ID) {}
9348 
9349  bool runOnMachineFunction(MachineFunction &MF) override {
9350  const X86TargetMachine *TM =
9351  static_cast<const X86TargetMachine *>(&MF.getTarget());
9352  const X86Subtarget &STI = MF.getSubtarget<X86Subtarget>();
9353 
9354  // Don't do anything in the 64-bit small and kernel code models. They use
9355  // RIP-relative addressing for everything.
9356  if (STI.is64Bit() && (TM->getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Small ||
9357  TM->getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Kernel))
9358  return false;
9359 
9360  // Only emit a global base reg in PIC mode.
9361  if (!TM->isPositionIndependent())
9362  return false;
9363 
9364  X86MachineFunctionInfo *X86FI = MF.getInfo<X86MachineFunctionInfo>();
9365  Register GlobalBaseReg = X86FI->getGlobalBaseReg();
9366 
9367  // If we didn't need a GlobalBaseReg, don't insert code.
9368  if (GlobalBaseReg == 0)
9369  return false;
9370 
9371  // Insert the set of GlobalBaseReg into the first MBB of the function
9372  MachineBasicBlock &FirstMBB = MF.front();
9373  MachineBasicBlock::iterator MBBI = FirstMBB.begin();
9374  DebugLoc DL = FirstMBB.findDebugLoc(MBBI);
9375  MachineRegisterInfo &RegInfo = MF.getRegInfo();
9376  const X86InstrInfo *TII = STI.getInstrInfo();
9377 
9378  Register PC;
9379  if (STI.isPICStyleGOT())
9380  PC = RegInfo.createVirtualRegister(&X86::GR32RegClass);
9381  else
9382  PC = GlobalBaseReg;
9383 
9384  if (STI.is64Bit()) {
9385  if (TM->getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Medium) {
9386  // In the medium code model, use a RIP-relative LEA to materialize the
9387  // GOT.
9388  BuildMI(FirstMBB, MBBI, DL, TII->get(X86::LEA64r), PC)
9389  .addReg(X86::RIP)
9390  .addImm(0)
9391  .addReg(0)
9392  .addExternalSymbol("_GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_")
9393  .addReg(0);
9394  } else if (TM->getCodeModel() == CodeModel::Large) {
9395  // In the large code model, we are aiming for this code, though the
9396  // register allocation may vary:
9397  // leaq .LN$pb(%rip), %rax
9398  // movq $_GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_ - .LN$pb, %rcx
9399  // addq %rcx, %rax
9400  // RAX now holds address of _GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_.
9401  Register PBReg = RegInfo.createVirtualRegister(&X86::GR64RegClass);
9402  Register GOTReg = RegInfo.createVirtualRegister(&X86::GR64RegClass);
9403  BuildMI(FirstMBB, MBBI, DL, TII->get(X86::LEA64r), PBReg)
9404  .addReg(X86::RIP)
9405  .addImm(0)
9406  .addReg(0)
9407  .addSym(MF.getPICBaseSymbol())
9408  .addReg(0);
9409  std::prev(MBBI)->setPreInstrSymbol(MF, MF.getPICBaseSymbol());
9410  BuildMI(FirstMBB, MBBI, DL, TII->get(X86::MOV64ri), GOTReg)
9411  .addExternalSymbol("_GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_",
9412  X86II::MO_PIC_BASE_OFFSET);
9413  BuildMI(FirstMBB, MBBI, DL, TII->get(X86::ADD64rr), PC)
9414  .addReg(PBReg, RegState::Kill)
9415  .addReg(GOTReg, RegState::Kill);
9416  } else {
9417  llvm_unreachable("unexpected code model");
9418  }
9419  } else {
9420  // Operand of MovePCtoStack is completely ignored by asm printer. It's
9421  // only used in JIT code emission as displacement to pc.
9422  BuildMI(FirstMBB, MBBI, DL, TII->get(X86::MOVPC32r), PC).addImm(0);
9423 
9424  // If we're using vanilla 'GOT' PIC style, we should use relative
9425  // addressing not to pc, but to _GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_ external.
9426  if (STI.isPICStyleGOT()) {
9427  // Generate addl $__GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_ + [.-piclabel],
9428  // %some_register
9429  BuildMI(FirstMBB, MBBI, DL, TII->get(X86::ADD32ri), GlobalBaseReg)
9430  .addReg(PC)
9431  .addExternalSymbol("_GLOBAL_OFFSET_TABLE_",
9432  X86II::MO_GOT_ABSOLUTE_ADDRESS);
9433  }
9434  }
9435 
9436  return true;
9437  }
9438 
9439  StringRef getPassName() const override {
9440  return "X86 PIC Global Base Reg Initialization";
9441  }
9442 
9443  void getAnalysisUsage(AnalysisUsage &AU) const override {
9444  AU.setPreservesCFG();
9445  MachineFunctionPass::getAnalysisUsage(AU);
9446  }
9447  };
9448 } // namespace
9449

9451 FunctionPass*
9452 llvm::createX86GlobalBaseRegPass() { return new CGBR(); }

9454 namespace {
9455  struct LDTLSCleanup : public MachineFunctionPass {
9456  static char ID;
9457  LDTLSCleanup() : MachineFunctionPass(ID) {}
9458 
9459  bool runOnMachineFunction(MachineFunction &MF) override {
9460  if (skipFunction(MF.getFunction()))
9461  return false;
9462 
9463  X86MachineFunctionInfo *MFI = MF.getInfo<X86MachineFunctionInfo>();
9464  if (MFI->getNumLocalDynamicTLSAccesses() < 2) {
9465  // No point folding accesses if there isn't at least two.
9466  return false;
9467  }
9468 
9469  MachineDominatorTree *DT = &getAnalysis<MachineDominatorTree>();
9470  return VisitNode(DT->getRootNode(), 0);
9471  }
9472 
9473  // Visit the dominator subtree rooted at Node in pre-order.
9474  // If TLSBaseAddrReg is non-null, then use that to replace any
9475  // TLS_base_addr instructions. Otherwise, create the register
9476  // when the first such instruction is seen, and then use it
9477  // as we encounter more instructions.
9478  bool VisitNode(MachineDomTreeNode *Node, unsigned TLSBaseAddrReg) {
9479  MachineBasicBlock *BB = Node->getBlock();
9480  bool Changed = false;
9481 
9482  // Traverse the current block.
9483  for (MachineBasicBlock::iterator I = BB->begin(), E = BB->end(); I != E;
9484  ++I) {
9485  switch (I->getOpcode()) {
9486  case X86::TLS_base_addr32:
9487  case X86::TLS_base_addr64:
9488  if (TLSBaseAddrReg)
9489  I = ReplaceTLSBaseAddrCall(*I, TLSBaseAddrReg);
9490  else
9491  I = SetRegister(*I, &TLSBaseAddrReg);
9492  Changed = true;
9493  break;
9494  default:
9495  break;
9496  }
9497  }
9498 
9499  // Visit the children of this block in the dominator tree.
9500  for (auto &I : *Node) {
9501  Changed |= VisitNode(I, TLSBaseAddrReg);
9502  }
9503 
9504  return Changed;
9505  }
9506 
9507  // Replace the TLS_base_addr instruction I with a copy from
9508  // TLSBaseAddrReg, returning the new instruction.
9509  MachineInstr *ReplaceTLSBaseAddrCall(MachineInstr &I,
9510  unsigned TLSBaseAddrReg) {
9511  MachineFunction *MF = I.getParent()->getParent();
9512  const X86Subtarget &STI = MF->getSubtarget<X86Subtarget>();
9513  const bool is64Bit = STI.is64Bit();
9514  const X86InstrInfo *TII = STI.getInstrInfo();
9515 
9516  // Insert a Copy from TLSBaseAddrReg to RAX/EAX.
9517  MachineInstr *Copy =
9518  BuildMI(*I.getParent(), I, I.getDebugLoc(),
9519  TII->get(TargetOpcode::COPY), is64Bit ? X86::RAX : X86::EAX)
9520  .addReg(TLSBaseAddrReg);
9521 
9522  // Erase the TLS_base_addr instruction.
9523  I.eraseFromParent();
9524 
9525  return Copy;
9526  }
9527 
9528  // Create a virtual register in *TLSBaseAddrReg, and populate it by
9529  // inserting a copy instruction after I. Returns the new instruction.
9530  MachineInstr *SetRegister(MachineInstr &I, unsigned *TLSBaseAddrReg) {
9531  MachineFunction *MF = I.getParent()->getParent();
9532  const X86Subtarget &STI = MF->getSubtarget<X86Subtarget>();
9533  const bool is64Bit = STI.is64Bit();
9534  const X86InstrInfo *TII = STI.getInstrInfo();
9535 
9536  // Create a virtual register for the TLS base address.
9537  MachineRegisterInfo &RegInfo = MF->getRegInfo();
9538  *TLSBaseAddrReg = RegInfo.createVirtualRegister(is64Bit
9539  ? &X86::GR64RegClass
9540  : &X86::GR32RegClass);
9541 
9542  // Insert a copy from RAX/EAX to TLSBaseAddrReg.
9543  MachineInstr *Next = I.getNextNode();
9544  MachineInstr *Copy =
9545  BuildMI(*I.getParent(), Next, I.getDebugLoc(),
9546  TII->get(TargetOpcode::COPY), *TLSBaseAddrReg)
9547  .addReg(is64Bit ? X86::RAX : X86::EAX);
9548 
9549  return Copy;
9550  }
9551 
9552  StringRef getPassName() const override {
9553  return "Local Dynamic TLS Access Clean-up";
9554  }
9555 
9556  void getAnalysisUsage(AnalysisUsage &AU) const override {
9557  AU.setPreservesCFG();
9558  AU.addRequired<MachineDominatorTree>();
9559  MachineFunctionPass::getAnalysisUsage(AU);
9560  }
9561  };
9562 }
9563 
9564 char LDTLSCleanup::ID = 0;
9565 FunctionPass*
9566 llvm::createCleanupLocalDynamicTLSPass() { return new LDTLSCleanup(); }
9567 
9568 /// Constants defining how certain sequences should be outlined.
9569 ///
9570 /// \p MachineOutlinerDefault implies that the function is called with a call
9571 /// instruction, and a return must be emitted for the outlined function frame.
9572 ///
9573 /// That is,
9574 ///
9575 /// I1 OUTLINED_FUNCTION:
9576 /// I2 --> call OUTLINED_FUNCTION I1
9577 /// I3 I2
9578 /// I3
9579 /// ret
9580 ///
9581 /// * Call construction overhead: 1 (call instruction)
9582 /// * Frame construction overhead: 1 (return instruction)
9583 ///
9584 /// \p MachineOutlinerTailCall implies that the function is being tail called.
9585 /// A jump is emitted instead of a call, and the return is already present in
9586 /// the outlined sequence. That is,
9587 ///
9588 /// I1 OUTLINED_FUNCTION:
9589 /// I2 --> jmp OUTLINED_FUNCTION I1
9590 /// ret I2
9591 /// ret
9592 ///
9593 /// * Call construction overhead: 1 (jump instruction)
9594 /// * Frame construction overhead: 0 (don't need to return)
9595 ///
9596 enum MachineOutlinerClass {
9597  MachineOutlinerDefault,
9598  MachineOutlinerTailCall
9599 };
9600 
9601 outliner::OutlinedFunction X86InstrInfo::getOutliningCandidateInfo(
9602  std::vector<outliner::Candidate> &RepeatedSequenceLocs) const {
9603  unsigned SequenceSize =
9604  std::accumulate(RepeatedSequenceLocs[0].front(),
9605  std::next(RepeatedSequenceLocs[0].back()), 0,
9606  [](unsigned Sum, const MachineInstr &MI) {
9607  // FIXME: x86 doesn't implement getInstSizeInBytes, so
9608  // we can't tell the cost. Just assume each instruction
9609  // is one byte.
9610  if (MI.isDebugInstr() || MI.isKill())
9611  return Sum;
9612  return Sum + 1;
9613  });
9614 
9615  // We check to see if CFI Instructions are present, and if they are
9616  // we find the number of CFI Instructions in the candidates.
9617  unsigned CFICount = 0;
9618  for (auto &I : make_range(RepeatedSequenceLocs[0].front(),
9619  std::next(RepeatedSequenceLocs[0].back()))) {
9620  if (I.isCFIInstruction())
9621  CFICount++;
9622  }
9623 
9624  // We compare the number of found CFI Instructions to the number of CFI
9625  // instructions in the parent function for each candidate. We must check this
9626  // since if we outline one of the CFI instructions in a function, we have to
9627  // outline them all for correctness. If we do not, the address offsets will be
9628  // incorrect between the two sections of the program.
9629  for (outliner::Candidate &C : RepeatedSequenceLocs) {
9630  std::vector<MCCFIInstruction> CFIInstructions =
9631  C.getMF()->getFrameInstructions();
9632 
9633  if (CFICount > 0 && CFICount != CFIInstructions.size())
9634  return outliner::OutlinedFunction();
9635  }
9636 
9637  // FIXME: Use real size in bytes for call and ret instructions.
9638  if (RepeatedSequenceLocs[0].back()->isTerminator()) {
9639  for (outliner::Candidate &C : RepeatedSequenceLocs)
9640  C.setCallInfo(MachineOutlinerTailCall, 1);
9641 
9642  return outliner::OutlinedFunction(RepeatedSequenceLocs, SequenceSize,
9643  0, // Number of bytes to emit frame.
9644  MachineOutlinerTailCall // Type of frame.
9645  );
9646  }
9647 
9648  if (CFICount > 0)
9649  return outliner::OutlinedFunction();
9650 
9651  for (outliner::Candidate &C : RepeatedSequenceLocs)
9652  C.setCallInfo(MachineOutlinerDefault, 1);
9653 
9654  return outliner::OutlinedFunction(RepeatedSequenceLocs, SequenceSize, 1,
9655  MachineOutlinerDefault);
9656 }
9657 
9658 bool X86InstrInfo::isFunctionSafeToOutlineFrom(MachineFunction &MF,
9659  bool OutlineFromLinkOnceODRs) const {
9660  const Function &F = MF.getFunction();
9661 
9662  // Does the function use a red zone? If it does, then we can't risk messing
9663  // with the stack.
9664  if (Subtarget.getFrameLowering()->has128ByteRedZone(MF)) {
9665  // It could have a red zone. If it does, then we don't want to touch it.
9666  const X86MachineFunctionInfo *X86FI = MF.getInfo<X86MachineFunctionInfo>();
9667  if (!X86FI || X86FI->getUsesRedZone())
9668  return false;
9669  }
9670 
9671  // If we *don't* want to outline from things that could potentially be deduped
9672  // then return false.
9673  if (!OutlineFromLinkOnceODRs && F.hasLinkOnceODRLinkage())
9674  return false;
9675 
9676  // This function is viable for outlining, so return true.
9677  return true;
9678 }
9679 
9680 outliner::InstrType
9681 X86InstrInfo::getOutliningTypeImpl(MachineBasicBlock::iterator &MIT, unsigned Flags) const {
9682  MachineInstr &MI = *MIT;
9683 
9684  // Is this a terminator for a basic block?
9685  if (MI.isTerminator())
9686  // TargetInstrInfo::getOutliningType has already filtered out anything
9687  // that would break this, so we can allow it here.
9688  return outliner::InstrType::Legal;
9689 
9690  // Don't outline anything that modifies or reads from the stack pointer.
9691  //
9692  // FIXME: There are instructions which are being manually built without
9693  // explicit uses/defs so we also have to check the MCInstrDesc. We should be
9694  // able to remove the extra checks once those are fixed up. For example,
9695  // sometimes we might get something like %rax = POP64r 1. This won't be
9696  // caught by modifiesRegister or readsRegister even though the instruction
9697  // really ought to be formed so that modifiesRegister/readsRegister would
9698  // catch it.
9699  if (MI.modifiesRegister(X86::RSP, &RI) || MI.readsRegister(X86::RSP, &RI) ||
9700  MI.getDesc().hasImplicitUseOfPhysReg(X86::RSP) ||
9701  MI.getDesc().hasImplicitDefOfPhysReg(X86::RSP))
9702  return outliner::InstrType::Illegal;
9703 
9704  // Outlined calls change the instruction pointer, so don't read from it.
9705  if (MI.readsRegister(X86::RIP, &RI) ||
9706  MI.getDesc().hasImplicitUseOfPhysReg(X86::RIP) ||
9707  MI.getDesc().hasImplicitDefOfPhysReg(X86::RIP))
9708  return outliner::InstrType::Illegal;
9709 
9710  // Don't outline CFI instructions.
9711  if (MI.isCFIInstruction())
9712  return outliner::InstrType::Illegal;
9713 
9714  return outliner::InstrType::Legal;
9715 }
9716 
9717 void X86InstrInfo::buildOutlinedFrame(MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
9718  MachineFunction &MF,
9719  const outliner::OutlinedFunction &OF)
9720  const {
9721  // If we're a tail call, we already have a return, so don't do anything.
9722  if (OF.FrameConstructionID == MachineOutlinerTailCall)
9723  return;
9724 
9725  // We're a normal call, so our sequence doesn't have a return instruction.
9726  // Add it in.
9727  MachineInstr *retq = BuildMI(MF, DebugLoc(), get(X86::RET64));
9728  MBB.insert(MBB.end(), retq);
9729 }
9730 
9731 MachineBasicBlock::iterator
9732 X86InstrInfo::insertOutlinedCall(Module &M, MachineBasicBlock &MBB,
9733  MachineBasicBlock::iterator &It,
9734  MachineFunction &MF,
9735  outliner::Candidate &C) const {
9736  // Is it a tail call?
9737  if (C.CallConstructionID == MachineOutlinerTailCall) {
9738  // Yes, just insert a JMP.
9739  It = MBB.insert(It,
9740  BuildMI(MF, DebugLoc(), get(X86::TAILJMPd64))
9741  .addGlobalAddress(M.getNamedValue(MF.getName())));
9742  } else {
9743  // No, insert a call.
9744  It = MBB.insert(It,
9745  BuildMI(MF, DebugLoc(), get(X86::CALL64pcrel32))
9746  .addGlobalAddress(M.getNamedValue(MF.getName())));
9747  }
9748 
9749  return It;
9750 }
